<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0001 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Canada Ink Nuclear Cooperation Protocol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- China and Canada signed a protocol
for technical cooperation and exchange of information in nuclear
regulatory matters here today.
</P>
<P>
Huang Qitao, director general of China's National Nuclear
Safety Administration (NNSA), and Agnes Bishop, president of the
Atomic Energy Control Board (AECB) of Canada, put their signatures
on the agreement at the AECB's headquarters here.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, the AECB will provide for nuclear
regulatory training and assistance to the NNSA and to provide for
the exchange of personnel.
</P>
<P>
Today's agreement represents the tenth of its kind China has
ever forged with other countries. It is a follow-up to the
Agreement for Cooperation in the Peaceful Uses of Nuclear Energy
between the two countries signed in November 1994.
</P>
<P>
The protocol becomes all the more important since the two
countries have agreed to build Candu 6 nuclear reactors in China,
Huang said.
</P>
<P>
Describing the accord as "important," Bishop said the agreement
is going to "be where both share and learn from each other" in the
nuclear safety field.
</P>
<P>
It has also opened "a door for a greater and promising future"
of Sino-Canadian cooperation in the peaceful use of nuclear
energy, added Chinese Ambassador to Canada Zhang Yijun, who
witnessed the signing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Beats China in International Basketball Challenge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Four-time Olympic veteran Oscar
Schmidt hit a game-high 25 points to lead the Brazil national team
to a 88-76 win over its Chinese opponent at the opening day of the
Beijing International Basketball Challenge here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 38-year-old World and Olympic top scorer sank three
3-pointers to key a 15-4 run which helped the Brazilians cut a
20-8 slow start to 24-20 before rallying to build 49-45 lead at
the break.
</P>
<P>
The Brazilians used a breathless physical defense and poured in
13 unanswered points to jump to a 62-45 lead in five minutes into
the the second half. They also outrebounded the Chinese national
side 30-25.
</P>
<P>
"We made things work on our defense," said the Brazilian coach
Carlos Rodrigues at the post-game press conference. "My team is
well known for the offense but we improved our defensing skills a
lot against China tonight."
</P>
<P>
The Brazil's well known offense forced three Chinese stars to
foul out and their improved defense held opponents' shooting to a
disappointing 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
In their last meet, underdog China scored a surprising victory
of 97-93 over Brazil and finished an ever best eighth place at the
1994 world championships in Toronto of Canada.
</P>
<P>
Both Brazil and China have qualifyed for this summer's Atlanta
Olympic Games and they are playing this tournament as warm-up
games prior to the opening ceremony on July 19.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the afternoon, the Klim All-Stars U.S. Team beat a
555 Chinese union side 105-84. Marc Brown hit 20 points to lead
five former NBA and Americans collegiate players finishing in
doubles figures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
