<HEADLINE> Italy, Spain Fined for Intertoto Withdrawls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- European soccer body UEFA fined the
Spanish and Italian soccer federations a total of 1.2 million
Swiss francs (1 million U.S. dollars) over their withdrawal of
clubs from the Intertoto Cup.
</P>
<P>
UEFA fined The Italian federation 900,000 francs (750,000
U.S. dollars) for withdrawing Parma, Roma, and Inter Milan from
the Intertoto competition.
</P>
<P>
The Spanish federation will have to pay 300,000 francs (240,000
dollars) for withdrawing its only team, Real Oviedo.
</P>
<P>
UEFA said further disciplinary measures would be discussed by
its Control and Disciplinary Commission.
</P>
<P>
Some 60 teams have entered the Intertoto Cup, which starts
later this month and gives clubs the chance to qualify for the
more prestigious UEFA Cup. 
</P>
