<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gasoline Prices Begin to Decline Across U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Gasoline prices in the U.S.,
which had increased quickly in the past several months, started
dropping recently at the pump stations, providing some relief for
U.S. consumers.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey by the Energy Information Administration
(EIA), an agency of the U.S. Energy Department, the price for a
gallon of regular unleaded gasoline fell by about 2.3 cents from
May 17 to June 5, to a national average of 126.5 cents.
</P>
<P>
But the price drop varies considerably by regions. For example,
the average price in the East Coast regions has fallen only about
one cent, while it fell 3.5 cents in the West Coast regions.
</P>
<P>
U.S. government analysts said that a buildup in conventional
gasoline supplies and declining crude oil prices are causing
prices to decline nationally.
</P>
<P>
They are expecting that the gasoline prices nationally will be
dropping much faster in the coming weeks because wholesale, spot
and future prices for gasoline have all plunged sharply.
</P>
<P>
In a separate report, the U.S. government said Wednesday that
U.S. firms are now free to buy crude oil that Iraq will be
permitted by the United Nations to sell over the next six months.
</P>
<P>
Gasoline prices in the U.S. had increased sharply from February
to early May and pushed the consumer prices index in the first
four months this year to an annual rate of 4.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton ordered on April 29 to sell about
12 million barrels of the nation's strategic oil reserves to
drive down the soaring gasoline prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
