<HEADLINE> Syrian President Calls for Tripartite Summit in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Syrian President Hafez al-Assad
has extended invitations to King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz of Saudi
Arabia and Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak to hold the
mini-summit in Damascus Friday.
</P>
<P>
The announcement came after Saudi Arabia denied that a
tripartite summit between King Fahd, Syrian President al-Assad and
Egyptian President Mubarak would be held in Riyadh Friday.
</P>
<P>
A Syrian official source has announced today that the
tripartite summit is scheduled to discuss the recommendations and
proposals submitted by the foreign ministers of the three
countries to their heads of states. They are related to the Arab
situation and the future of the peace process in light of the
latest developments in the region.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers from the three countries held two
rounds of talks in Riyadh to work out the outlines and mechanisms
for future common Arab action and for strengthening the position
of Arab negotiators in view of the victory of right wing Likud
leader Benjamin Netanyahu in the Israeli elections.
</P>
<P>
The coming tripartite summit will be the latest of a flurry of
diplomatic activity aimed at coordinating Arab stances following
Netanyahu's election victory.
</P>
<P>
Syrian President al-Assad held a meeting with Lebanese
President Elias Hrawi in Syria Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Mubarak and his Syrian counterpart al-Assad
held a meeting in Cairo Monday and Mubarak, King Hussein of Jordan
and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat held a tripartite summit in
the Jordanian Red Sea resort of Aqaba Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
