<HEADLINE> Mandela Postpones State Visit to Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 6 (Xinhua) -- President Nelson Mandela's
first state visit to Angola has been postponed, the South African
Press Association reported today.
</P>
<P>
Mandela was due to visit that country from June 11 to 13 at
the invitation of Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued by the President's Office in Cape Town,
Mandela demanded the visit be rescheduled and the Angolan
government was informed of the demand this morning.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo had been instructed by the
president to visit Angola on Monday to convey ''a personal
message'' to dos Santos, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
According to presidential spokesman Parks Mankahlana, Mandela
believed it would be inconsiderate to impose a state visit on his
Angolan counterpart, ''who was currently grappling with a transition
in government''.
</P>
<P>
Mankahlana said the president had also told dos Santos that he
would ''do all in his power to assist the peace process in Angola''.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, dos Santos dismissed his Prime Minister
Marcolinao Moco and suspended all foreign exchange operations in
response to the country's deep economic and social crisis.
</P>
<P>
He also appointed Fernando Franca van Dunem, President of the
National Assembly, as the new prime minister and gave him five days
to form a new government. enditem

