<HEADLINE> Netanyahu: He Plans to Hold Peace Talks with Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister-elect
Benjamin Netanyahu said today that he plans to hold peace
negotiations with Syria and to reduce tensions between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made the remarks to reporters during a visit to the
Haifa Municipality to thank the people of the city to vote for him
in the May 29 Israeli general elections.
</P>
<P>
He said he has new ideas to conduct peace talks with Syria and
to take steps to build mutual confidence, however, he refused to
go into any details.
</P>
<P>
On the Palestinian track, Netanyahu said his government will
enter permanent status talks in which Israel and the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) will clarify their positions.
</P>
<P>
He also said he was encouraged by what he called "the positive
reactions" he received from the Arab world following his victory
in the prime ministerial election.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, chairman of the Likud Party, defeated incumbent
Prime Minister Shimon Peres with a narrow lead of less than one
percent in last week's elections, and will become the first
directly elected Israeli premier.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after his victory, he received an invitation from
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak to visit Cairo, capital of
Egypt after he forms his new government.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, he also sent his top foreign policy aide
Dore Gold to Jordan to meet King Hussein, before Hussein, Mubarak
and PNA President Yasser Arafat met in Jordan's Red Sea resort of
Aqaba Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In his victory speech on Sunday, he said he was extending his
hand of conciliation to Arab leaders, calling on them to continue
to walk down the path of peace.
</P>
<P>
"We intend to further the process of dialogue with all of our
neighbors to reach a stable peace, a real peace, a peace with
security," he said.
</P>
<P>
However, it appears that Israel's Arab neighbors have been
concerned about Netanyahu's views on regional affairs and his hard
line policies which he had been stressing during his campaigns for
the elections.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Syrian President Hafez al-Assad has
invited Egyptian President Mubarak and King Fahd of Saudi Arabia
to meet in Damascus Friday to discuss the future of the Middle
East peace process in the wake of Netanyahu's election victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
