<HEADLINE> ValueJet's Passenger Load Falls Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 6 (Xinhua) -- ValuJet Inc., a small domestic
airline runner which has suffered from a crash of one of its
planes last month that killed 110 people, said its planes flew
almost half empty in May.
</P>
<P>
The low-fare, no-frills airline reported that its load factor
-- or percentage of seats sold -- was 52.7 percent last month,
down from 71.5 percent for May 1995, according to the Investor's
Business Daily today. In April, ValuJet's load factor was 61.8
percent, it said.
</P>
<P>
"The traffic rebuilding will be slow and arduous," said Samuel
Buttrick, an analyst at PaineWebber, a noted investment and
research company.
</P>
<P>
In May, ValuJet's passenger transport fell 7.4 percent to
378,600 from 409,130, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The plane crash of the Atlanta-based airline in May reignited
the nation-wide concern about the safety of small and medium-sized
airlines, who are competing for bigger market share by cutting air
fares. The crash has also brought losses to other similar
companies as more passengers are walking away from them.
</P>
<P>
People are paying greater attention to their safety record
and ages of the planes in service. And share prices of ValuJet
declined remarkably on Wall Street. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Press Freedom in HK Will Be Guaranteed: Chinese Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Freedom of the press in Hong Kong
will be guaranteed by law after its return to Chinese rule in July
1997, a Chinese senior official said today.
</P>
<P>
"The Basic Law on Hong Kong guarantees freedom of the press,
speech, assembly, association and religion," Lu Ping, director of
the Hong Kong and Macao Affairs Office under China's State
Council, told a press conference in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
But he said Beijing will not allow any actions that aim to
overthrow the Chinese government or to divide China.
</P>
<P>
Lu is on a week-long visit to Japan through Saturday at the
invitation of the Japanese Foreign Ministry. The purpose of his
trip is to explain China's policy on Hong Kong to Japanese
political and business leaders.
</P>
<P>
He criticized biased reports by some overseas news
organizations, saying, "if you want to quote me, please quote all
I have said instead of just some words or half a sentence."
</P>
<P>
Asked about democracy in Hong Kong, Lu said, "I believe July 1,
1997 will be the start of true democracy in Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
During Britain's colonial rule of around 100 years, Hong Kong
has not enjoyed any form of real democracy because its governor is
appointed by the British Queen and its legislators are named by
the governor, he noted.
</P>
<P>
After the 1997 hand-over, all legislators and even the chief
secretary in Hong Kong will be elected, not appointed, he added.
</P>
<P>
Lu also expressed the hope that Beijing and London will
cooperate closely over Hong Kong's reversion to Chinese
sovereignty and urged foreign countries, especially Japan, to
continue investing in Hong Kong to keep it prosperous. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
