<HEADLINE> Swaziland Scraps Increased Post, Phone Tariffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Swaziland cabinet has
scrapped the 15 percent tariff increase for post and
telecommunications services, the South African Press Association
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The tariff increases was announced by the Swaziland Post and
Telecommunications Corporation last month, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a television news broadcast last night in the
capital Mbabane, Acting Prime Minister Sishayi Nxumalo said
subscribers, particularly among the business community, protested
against the increase which exceeded the 9.9 percent maximum
stipulated by law.
</P>
<P>
Nxumalo said the corporation had acted illegally in exceeding
the limit without the approval of the Standing Committee on
Public Enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The corporation had been ordered by the cabinet that all
subscribers be refunded money they had paid in terms of the
increase.
</P>
<P>
Nxumalo also stressed that an inquiry into the increase was to
be held and unless those responsible provided a satisfactory
explanation, they would face disciplinary action. enditem

