<HEADLINE> Britain Supports Zimbabwe's Economic Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 5 (Xinhua) -- Britain today pledged its continued
support for Zimbabwe's efforts to reform the economy and acquire
mainly white-owned commercial farms to resettle thousands of
landless peasants.
</P>
<P>
The assurance was given by visiting British Overseas
Development Minister Baroness Lynda Chalker after her talks with
Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe in Harare today.
</P>
<P>
She did not, however, say how much Londond was prepared to
provide for the reforms or the land acquisition program.
</P>
<P>
Chalker, who is also Minister of Foreign and Commonwealth
Affairs, told journalists after a 90-minute meeting with Mugabe
that she was confident Zimbabwe could achieve real economic growth.
</P>
<P>
She said the British government would continue to discuss with
Zimbabwe the controversial land issue in the country with a view
to seeing how it could assist in redressing the land imbalances.
</P>
<P>
The Land Acquisition Act, enacted in 1992, provides for the
designation and compulsory acquisition of agricultural land for
resettlement of thousands of landless blacks.
</P>
<P>
On South Africa's relations with its neighbors, Chalker said:
"South Africa needs to work with its neighbors, otherwise there
will be no economic success. My government will do its best to
bring South Africa and Zimbabwe together," she said. 
</P>
