<HEADLINE> Namibia Calls for Help to AIDS Orphans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Namibian Health and Social
Services Minister Nickey Iyambo has appealed for help to children
orphaned by AIDS, the South African Press Association reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Iyambo made the appeal in Windhoek on Wednesday at the
hand-over of a mobile clinic by the Norwegian embassy to the AIDS
Care Trust of the country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking about children abandoned at a state hospital in
Windhoek after their mothers died from the diseases shortly after
giving birth, the minister said: "they are being cared for at the
hospital although they are not sick because their relatives do
not want them."
</P>
<P>
According to unofficial statistics, about 500 Namibians are
being infected with HIV that causes AIDS each day.
</P>
<P>
Iyambo said there are 20,177 reported cases of HIV infection
in the country, compared with only 1,000 three years ago.
</P>
<P>
"We must show these people love and encouragement so that they
feel they are not rejected by their fellow citizens," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, President Sam Nujoma also appealed to the nation not
to discriminate against AIDS sufferers and called on those
infected to come forward and warn others about the disease.
</P>
<P>
"The example set by some of our infected citizens is an act of
bravery," said the president. 
</P>
