<HEADLINE> Government Chooses Site for Third Paris Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Paris, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The French government announced today
that Paris' third airport will be built at a site about 80
kilometers southwest of this capital.
</P>
<P>
The planned new airport, at Beauvilliers near the city of
Chartres, will supplement the existing facilities of
Roissy-Charles de Gaulle and Orly.
</P>
<P>
However, according to Transport Minister Bernard Pons,
construction of the new facility is not expected to be completed
until the year 2015 at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
Among other candidates, the chosen site would presumably cause
the least environmental and other problems.
</P>
<P>
About 50 million air passengers currently use the existing two
airports annually, making Paris the second largest hub in Europe
and the seventh in the world.
</P>
<P>
A Transport Ministry report issued in July said that the demand
would be between 76 and 96 million passengers by the year 2015,
and 90 to 124 million by 2030.
</P>
<P>
It warned that if without a new airport, Paris could lose the
additional passengers to other cities in Western Europe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
