<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France, Germany Devise Joint Defense Strategy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 5 (Xinhua) -- France and Germany, both Europe's
powerhouses, today agreed to work out a joint strategic policy on
defense by this Autumn, in a bid to iron out their differences
over the issue.
</P>
<P>
President Jacques Chirac and Chancellor Helmut Kohl made the
decision at the 67th Franco-German summit held today in Dijon,
eastern France.
</P>
<P>
The joint framework for defense will set out their common
strategic interests as a basis for future cooperation, said a
statement.
</P>
<P>
Both Chirac and Kohl agreed that the two countries should
review their armament cooperation and military integration,
according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
They did not give details of the common strategic policy to
reporters. Kohl said that it needs "discussions."
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, the two leaders will sign a final
document on military strategy, armed forces and armament policy at
their next summit scheduled in December.
</P>
<P>
Chirac told reporters that they had no "misunderstandings" that
were caused by the radical reforms on French defense policy he
declared in February, shifting to an all-professional army,
scrapping conscription and cutting the military budget.
</P>
<P>
France has announced it will give up developing a type of
military air-freighter worth 4.5 to 7 billion francs (about 0.9 to
1.4 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Germany, who had feared that Paris' defense reforms will do
harm to some jointly developed weapon systems, has agreed with
Chirac's move in the development of aircraft.
</P>
<P>
During the summit, French Defense Minister Charles Millon and
his German counterpart Volker Ruehe signed an agreement,
instructing a Franco-German working group to examine the 27
existing joint armament programs.
</P>
<P>
Bonn has reiterated that Germany will press ahead with a
military intelligence satellite system to be jointly built with
France.
</P>
<P>
On the nuclear issue, Kohl said Germany has no intention to get
nuclear weapons through France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
