<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WWF Urges Effort to Save Marine Fishes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The World Wide Fund for Nature (WWF)
Thursday urged efforts to stop global overfishing in order to
reverse the crisis in marine fisheries and to restore abundant
seas.
</P>
<P>
It said it is planning to invest over 1 million dollars
annually to build the necessary political will globally to take
steps to save marine fishes, including halt to overfishing and
reduced use of destructive fishing practices.
</P>
<P>
It quoted the United Nations Food and Agriculture Organization
(FAO) as reporting that 70 percent of the world's commercially
important marine fish stocks are either fully fished,
overexploited, depleted, or slowly recovering.
</P>
<P>
In addition, indiscriminate fishing practices kill and waste
fully one-third of world catch --between 18 and 40 million tons
of unwanted fish, seabirds, sea turtles, marine mammals and other
ocean life every year, threatening the marine biological diversity.
</P>
<P>
Overfishing has reduced spawning populations of many of the
large ocean-wandering predators such as tunas, swordfish, marlins
and sharks, by more than 80 percent in the past two decades, said
WWF, the formerly World Wildlife Fund based in Gland, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
In some areas, staple species such as Atlantic cod and Atlantic
halibut have become commercially extinct. In 1993, the Canadian
cod fishery was shut down off the Grand Banks, resulting in the
losses of more than 40,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
According to WWF, about 1.2 million commercial vessels are
scouring the world's oceans today. Increasingly volatile "fish
wars" occurred due to disputes over the remnants of rapidly
declining stocks, the most notorious recently of them the
Canadian-Spanish "turbot war" in early 1995.
</P>
<P>
Many fleets of developed countries are now plundering the
fishing grounds of developing countries after overfishing their
own waters. The European Union (EU) now gets more than 25 percent
of its catch from outside its home waters.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, EU spent more than one-third of its fisheries budget
to subsidize access to foreign fishing grounds. Globally, the
governments pay a total of 54 billion U.S. dollars a year in
subsidizing the 70 billion dollar-worth fishery industry.
</P>
<P>
WWF said fishing fleets should be cut to allow the recovery of
fish resources. The EU has about 40 percent more vessels than
necessary to catch fish on a sustainable basis, it added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0030 </DOCNO>
