<HEADLINE> UN Seeks 43.6 Million Dollars in Aid to DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Thursday
appealed for over 43.6 million U.S. dollars in addressing the
humanitarian emergencies in the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK) arising from the devastating floods last year.
</P>
<P>
The UN consolidated inter-agency appeal covers the period from
July 1 1996 to the end of March 1997, focusing on the three
priority sectors of food aid, the recovery of arable lands and
health.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 27 million dollars of the funds will address the food
crisis in the country, where flooding destroyed about 1.5 million
tons of grain harvest and stocks, and a shortfall of some 1.9
million tons of cereals is predicted by experts for the year
1996.
</P>
<P>
Some 10.3 million dollars are sought for the recovery of arable
lands in order to resume normal agricultural production and ease
the food shortages. Floods had damaged an estimated 360,000
hectares of arable lands in DPRK, it is reported.
</P>
<P>
It accounts for nearly 6 million dollars of the appealed money
to restore the DPRK's basic health services, which had been
severely disrupted by the floods.  
</P>
</TEXT>
