<HEADLINE> Swiss Banks Managed 2,340 Billion SFrs - Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- A recent study showed that assets
managed by the banks in Switzerland totaled about 2,340 billion
Swiss francs (some 1,900 billion U.S. dollars) in 1994, local
press reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The study also noted that the assets management branch of Swiss
banking industry employed 50,000 out of the totled 140,000 bank
employees, providing more jobs than the watch-making and jewelery
industry.
</P>
<P>
The study was conducted by the Basel-based Institute for Labour
Market and Industry Economics in order to assess the importance of
the assets management branch to the Swiss banking industry as well
as to the Swiss economy.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, it revealed, assets management accounted for about two
thirds of all Swiss banks' net profits, and for nearly a quarter
of the total export profits of Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland's three largest banks, namely the Union Bank,
Credit Suisse and Swiss Bank Corp., took the lion's share of all
the assets management business in 1994, followed by Swiss-based
foreign-controlled banks, trade banks and cantonal banks.
</P>
<P>
About 65 percent of the fortune managed by Swiss banks came
from private clients, and half of the total from foreign clients,
according to the study.  
</P>
</TEXT>
