<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean President Lashes Out at Racist Whites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
today once again lashed out at racist white minorities, saying
they are ignoring an extended hand of friendship from the
government by holding to their discriminatory attitudes.
</P>
<P>
He said while the government had adopted the policy of
reconciliation with those who fought against the freedom of
blacks, the whites had never showed any remorse over their
colonial activities.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at the burial of former freedom fighter
Stanford Tofa Shamu who died on June 2.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said while those who supported colonial rule had been
forgiven, they had not reciprocated but rather became more racial
in attitude.
</P>
<P>
"Racism in attitude and in its expression in economic and
other historical imbalances must go, and go now, now, now and
never to be found again," said Mugabe, adding only this could
lead to national oneness as both blacks and whites sought a
common destiny in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"The land they took from us by force, they refuse to give it
up," said Mugabe, referring to some white commercial farmers who
have challenged the government's compulsory acquisition of their
farms.
</P>
<P>
Through the Land Acquisition Act of 1992, the government has
given itself power to acquire land from some commercial farmers
so that it could be distributed to needy blacks.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe urged blacks and whites in the nation to come together
and ensure that racial division does not continue. 
</P>
