<HEADLINE> Energy Star Program Launched in US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Energy Department and the
Environmental Protection Agency have jointly launched Energy Star
program to lower energy consumption, save money for consumers and
cut pollution, according to local press reports.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, manufacturers of appliances and building
materials would be offered the right to use a government seal of
approval, the Energy Star, if their products meet federal
efficiency standards.
</P>
<P>
The program will focus on products used in buildings, which
account for one-third of the country's energy consumption and
two-thirds of its electricity use.
</P>
<P>
The logo, a green and blue globe, appears over the motto:
Saving the Earth. Saving Your Money.
</P>
<P>
"Within a year or two, the Energy Star label will be as
commonplace and sought-after as those other labels," said David
Nemtzow, the president of the Alliance to Save Energy, a
non-profit group that is working with the Federal agencies to
expand the Energy Star program beyond computers.
</P>
<P>
the agencies plan to begin the program in San Francisco, Tampa,
Milwakee and Washington and then have it spread nationwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
