<HEADLINE> Iran Supports Oil Sales by Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian government today once
again expressed its support for oil sales by Iraq at the OPEC's
ministerial meeting in Vienna, which started on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Oil Minister Gholamreza Aqazadeh said: "Iraq should be
allowed to supply oil to the international market without
adversely affecting the market price."
</P>
<P>
"The situation would warrant cooperation among all OPEC
members," the Iranian oil minister was quoted by Iran's official
news agency IRNA as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian minister also called on the member states of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) to observe
their own assigned quotas in order to ensure a stable world market.
</P>
<P>
After months of negotiations, an agreement on limited sale of
Iraqi oil was signed by the Iraqi government and the United
Nations last month.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Iraq is allowed to export up to 2 billion
U.S. dollars worth of oil for an initial six-month period to buy
food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that Iran, the second largest oil
exporting country in the world, supports Iraqi oil sales because
it maintains that the Iraqi oil sales would not affect its own oil
sales or cause reduction of Iran's oil revenues.
</P>
<P>
They said that the Iranian support for resumptions of Iraqi oil
sales might have positive impact upon the relations between
Tehran and Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Tehran holds that the resumption of Iraqi oil sales will help
the two neighboring countries thwart the dual-containment policy
by the United States.
</P>
<P>
Iranian President Hashemi Rafsanjani has publicly expressed
sympathy with the oppressed people of Iraq without mentioning the
Iraqi government by name.
</P>
<P>
He said, "the situation of the Moslem people in Iraq is
completely undesirable. Although we believe that the international
regulations and resolutions should be implemented, yet attention
should be paid to saving the Iraqi nation from the present
condition and its plight." 
</P>
</TEXT>
