<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Post-War Reconstruction Makes Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(By Pei Shanqin)
</P>
<P>
KIGALI, June 5 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan national unity
government has made remarkable progress in promoting national
reconciliation and reconstruction since it came to power on July
19, 1994.
</P>
<P>
Former president Juvenal Habyarimana, a member of of the Hutu
ethnic majority, was killed in April 1994 when his plane was shot
down as it flew into Kigali. His death led to three months of
ethnic bloodletting, in which 500,000 people were killed and one
million displaced, before the Tutsi-led Rwandan Patriotic Front
(RPF) seized power the following July.
</P>
<P>
Due to the catastrophe, the social order was destroyed, the
public activities disabled throughout the country, and its
national economy given a fatal strike.
</P>
<P>
Under this situation, the newly-founded national unity
government, in which Rwanda Patriotic Front (RPF) plays a leading
role, was facing many a challenge to overcome in the small
mountainous country.
</P>
<P>
As soon as the new government was established, it embarked on
a reconstruction and development program and set out an overall
strategy to promote national unity and reconciliation, social
welfare and economic prosperity.
</P>
<P>
To create and maintain peace and stability in the country, the
government has also taken some concrete measures, such as
suspension of political party's activities, rehabilitation and
strengthening judicial organizations, and proper settlement of
displaced people and returned refugees.
</P>
<P>
So far, government departments at all levels have been
re-established and strengthened. The state of security has been
greatly improved and peace basicly realized in the country,
although there are still some harassing and wrecking activities
conducted in the western area by former government armed elements
who infiltrated from neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
The comparative stability in the country has created good
conditions for returning of refugees.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, since the end of the civil
war and genocide, 1.8 million Rwandese refugees have returned
home from neighboring Uganda, Tanzania, Burundi and Zaire.
</P>
<P>
With assistance from U.N. and international organizations, the
government has established some refugee transit camps along
border areas and built houses, drinking water facilities, schools
and health centers in planned settlement areas.
</P>
<P>
In return, the proper settlement of displaced people and
refugees has played a positive role for social stability in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the economy, which was in ruins two years ago, now
has been recovering.
</P>
<P>
A senior official in the Planning Ministry said that Gross
Domestic Product in 1995 increased by 25 percent in comparison
with that of 1994, and reached 60 percent of that of 1990 when
the civil war first broke out.
</P>
<P>
Last year the agricultural production rose to 60 to 80 percent
of pre-war rates. Food production was recorded at 3.1 million
tonnes last year as against 5 million tonnes in 1990.
</P>
<P>
In the industrial sector, 54 of the total 88 enterprise
factories in the country have been re-operated, production of
which achieved 75 percent of the pre-war level.
</P>
<P>
Since last October, exchange rates of the Rwanda Franc against
foreign currencies have been stable, with the soaring trend of
the prices controlled and the annual inflation rate stablized at
about 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
The government has also attached much importance to
rehabilitation of basic infrastructure and social welfare
projects.
</P>
<P>
According to the Minister for Rehabilitation and Social
Integration Patrick Mazimhaka, all major roads and communications
in the country have been restored, and electricity and water
supplies are now available in all 13 urban centers and in 80
percent of rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The health sector is also recovering after the devastation of
the war and genocide. In 1994, there were 284 health centers in
the country, most of them were damaged, but two years later, 270
are now back in operation and 29 out of its 33 hospitals are
functioning again.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the determined effort and co-operation between
the government and the international community, schools now
function in all areas of the country and more than one million
Rwandan children attended school in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Achievements scored in the post-war reconstruction, of course,
have further consolidated political power of the new government.
</P>
<P>
However, it should be noted that such reconstruction and
rehabilitation in full scale is still facing a lot of
difficulties, such as lack of funds, technicians and skilled
manpower and harassing and subversion activities conducted by
former government armed elements in the western areas.
</P>
<P>
There is a lot to be done to realize final national
reconciliation, because about 1.5 million refugees are still in
neighboring countries, majority of whom are Hutus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwandan Prime Minister on Foreign Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(By Pei Shanqin)
</P>
<P>
KIGALI, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The foreign policy of the Rwandan
national unity government is door-open and friendly to all
peace-loving countries, especially to those which helped Rwandan
people during the civil war and their struggle agaisnt genocide.
</P>
<P>
The statements were made by Rwandan Prime Minister Pierre
Celestin Rwigyema here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister told Xinhua that since the new government
was established on July 19, 1994, Rwanda has made a success on
the diplomatic front, with assistance from the international
community in its post-war reconstruction and rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
Rwigema said that the number of diplomatic missions based in
Kigali is now increasing.
</P>
<P>
On ties between Rwanda and neighboring countries, the prime
minister said that Rwanda is practicing a good-neighborliness
policy, stressing that Rwanda wants to be a good friend to all
neighboring countries so as to have a good regional environment
for the post-war reconstruction of the country.
</P>
<P>
With Burundi, he said, there is no problem. Burundi is now
experiencing a difficult time of some internal problems. "Our
wishes are to see the international community to help the
Burundian people to avoid the tragedy occurred in Rwanda," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
On relations between Rwanda and Tanzania, Rwigema said, the
relations between the two countries are good.
</P>
<P>
He said that the relations were strengthened after recent
visits to Tanzania by Rwandan foreign minister and himself. The
Tanzanian government has promised to co-operate with Rwanda to
help solving difficulties in road transportation and
communications it faces at present.
</P>
<P>
Rwigema said that Tanzania would also help repatriating
Rwandan refugees. Some Rwandan ministers will visit Rwandan
refugee camps in North-Western Tanzania to explain the government
policy, peaceful situation in the country and needs for their
returning back home for the post-war reconstruction, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said he believed that more and more refugees will come back
home.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said, Uganda, as Tanzania, is a good friend
of Rwanda. "The relations between Rwanda and Uganda are
excellent," he said.
</P>
<P>
On relations between Rwanda and Zaire, Rwigema said, the
relations are "not so good, nor bad" , because there is some
misunderstandings about the Rwandan properties or equipments
looted to Zaire by the former Rwandan government and army, and a
large number of the former government officials and military
officers are genocide authors.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister expressed the hope that one day the problem of
misunderstanding will be solved through friendly discussions
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"I have invited my Zairean counterpart to visit Rwanda, and
even the Zairean prime minister himself has expressed his hope to
come to Rwanda last month when he visited Burundi," he added.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the prime minister said that Rwanda will try
its best to contribute to stability and economic development in
the sub-region through the meetings organized in the region,
which he believed, are one of the means to be able to promote
peace and stability in the sub-region.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
