<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hundreds of Homes Destroyed in Alaska Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The fire started over the weekend in the Big Lake areas, some
60 miles north of Anchorage, and as many as a third of the 2,000
homes in the area were damaged or destroyed, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Plumes of flame shot 200 feet high and the forest was shrouded
in thick smoke that drifted down to Anchorage, where officials
have issued an air quality alert.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the advancing blaze of the fire forced the state
Department of Corrections to evacuate the 74 inmates of the Point
MacKenzie prison farm and troops have closed periodically the
Parks Highway, the only highway between Anchorage and Fairbanks.
</P>
<P>
On the Alaska Railroad, southbound trains out of Fairbanks were
halted because the fire burned right up to the tracks.
</P>
<P>
Fanned by strong wind, the fire continued growing Thursday and
some 1,100 firefighters from other states were due to arrive
Thursday afternoon to reinforce the 500 crews, who have battled the
blaze for up to five days.
</P>
<P>
Airplanes and helicopters dropped water and fire retardant, but
the chemical has not been effective on the burning moss on the
forest floor.
</P>
<P>
With rain not expected before Sunday, there was no end in sight
to the blaze. Fire officials said more homes could be lost if the
fire jumps eastward across the Parks Highway and makes the 10-mile
trip to Wasilla, a town of 4,800. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
