<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Warns Against Use of Force by Liberians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 7 (Xinhua) -- West Africa's sub-regional grouping,
ECOWAS, announced here today that it would not back any Liberian
government that comes into office through the use of force.
</P>
<P>
In a press release reaching here today, the Economic Community
of West African States (ECOWAS) said any such act is in violation
of the peace accord signed in Abuja, capital of Nigeria last
August.
</P>
<P>
The proposed general elections on August 20 this year must be
held as scheduled, the release said, calling for the cooperation
of the factional leaders and people in liberia.
</P>
<P>
The west African heads of state have agreed that there is a
need to reinforce the regional peacepeeping forces, the ECOMOG,
in a bid to enhance its role in the west African country torn
apart by over six years of civil war, according to the ECOWAS
source.
</P>
<P>
On the alleged boycott by most of the west African leaders on
the failed heads of state and government summit meeting on
Liberia earlier in May, the ECOWAS said that was a false report.
</P>
<P>
The regional leaders deliberately stayed away from the
proposed summit of May 8, having earlier decided that the issues
under deliberation were within the competence of their foreign
ministers, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS first intervened in the Liberian crisis in August 1990
when it started to send a sub-regional monitor mission to
Monrovia to enforce a ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
However, it failed to stop the escalation of war which dragged
on for another six years.
</P>
<P>
Until August 20, 1995, when the warlords in Liberia signed the
Abuja peace accord which provides for the establishment of an
interim government and a ceasefire.
</P>
<P>
With the latest round of armed clashes in Monrovia, the
relevant sides began to search for new and more effective ways
which can lead the west African country to a permament peace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
