<HEADLINE> Ningbo to Render Obsolete Public Toilets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NINGBO, June 7 (Xinhua) -- This small city in east China's
Zhejiang Province has decided to make primitive public toilets a
thing of the past through the use of ecological technology.
</P>
<P>
It has built its first public toilet using an ecological
purifying technique that ferments methane anaerobe.
</P>
<P>
The public toilet has an area of 180 sq m and a distinct design.
</P>
<P>
The city now has a permanent population of 900,000, and
discharges about 600,000 tons of domestic sewage and industrial
liquid waste annually.
</P>
<P>
A survey showed that 80 percent of the toilets where the
technique is adopted meet approved state standards for waste
discharge.
</P>
<P>
This February, the municipal government issued a notice that
stipulated the technique is to be used for public toilets in all
apartment buildings in the future.  
</P>
</TEXT>
