<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 10:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Urges Access to Reliable Health Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISTANBUL, June 7 (Xinhua) -- A World Health Organization (WHO)
official voiced here today the emphasis on access to reliable
health care for everyone, especially the most deprived.
</P>
<P>
"WHO's main concern is to help countries and cities to ensure
access to reliable health care and services of good quality for
every one, with special emphasis on meeting the needs of the most
deprived," said Hiroshi Nakajima, WHO's Director-General, at
today's session of the ongoing Second United Nations Conference
on Human Settlements (HABITAT II).
</P>
<P>
To achieve this goal in urban areas, Nakajima said, WHO
proposed efforts to focus particularly on creating a healthy
environment, responding to specific health emergencies and
promoting lifestyles that are conducive to health.
</P>
<P>
The WHO chief explained that inadequate housing and
infrastructure are major factors of disease and
ill-health. Meanwhile, unmanaged population growth and
industrialization are also causing climate changes and rising
levels of pollution.
</P>
<P>
Nakajima also underlined the importance of educating the youth
to adopt more healthy lifestyles, which can reduce disease and
disability later in life.
</P>
<P>
WHO urged health systems to be redesigned to ensure that
services can be brought to the people.
</P>
<P>
Nakajima said that the challenge for HABITAT II, also known as
"City Summit," is to find ways in which cities can be both
prosperous and environment-friendly and, at the same time, places
where the dignity, the health and the well-being of all people
can be protected and enhanced.
</P>
<P>
"This will be achieved through local effectiveness and global
solidarity," Nakajima concluded.
</P>
<P>
A dialogue called "Creating Healthy Cities in the 21st Century"
was also organized by WHO today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
