<HEADLINE> Vietnam-U.S. Trade Ties Have Developed but Still </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Trade ties between Vietnam and the
United States have developed since the two countries established
diplomatic relations last July, but still face problems, official
Vietnam News Agency (VNA) said in report here today.
</P>
<P>
VNA said the U.S. now ranks sixth in terms of foreign
investment in Vietnam with 53 projects licensed with a combined
investment capital of 1,153 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's total export turnover to the U.S. reached 199 million
dollars in 1995, four times higher than the previous year, VNA
said. At present, 20 items from Vietnam are exported to the U.S.
market, including household utensils, handicrafts, art articles,
precious stones, food, toys and sports ware.
</P>
<P>
VNA noted that trade relations between the two countries also
saw limitations due to an absence of a trade accord which will
serve as the legal basis for bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
"Worse still", it stressed, " the U.S. has not yet granted most
favoured nation (mfn) status to Vietnam, which makes Vietnam's
exports to the U.S. less competitive due to high duties."
</P>
<P>
Vietnam is striving hard to improve the quality and diversity
of its export items in order to win a firm foothold in the
U.S. market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
