<HEADLINE> Xinhua International News Summary at 1100 GMT on June 7 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA -- The United Nations Thursday appealed for over 43.6
million U.S. dollars in addressing the humanitarian emergencies in
the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) arising from the
devastating floods last year.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Syrian President Hafez al-Assad has extended
invitations to King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz of Saudi Arabia and
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak to hold the mini-summit in
Damascus Friday.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister-elect Benjamin Netanyahu
said Thursday that he plans to hold peace negotiations with Syria
and to reduce tensions between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Talks on forming Israel's new coalition
government have been stalled over tough demands of the religious
parties who want to reverse the religious status quo to that
before 1992.
</P>
<P>
KAMPALA -- Twenty-three Uganda People's Defence Forces (UPDF)
soldiers were killed on Thursday at Owero, 20 miles on Gulu-Kitgum
road, northern Uganda, in an ambush by rebels of the Lord's
Resistance Army (LRA).
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Leader of the four-party Afghan opposition
alliance Sibghatullah Mojaddedi has decided to terminate the
membership of Hezb-i-Islami (Hekmatyar Group) from the alliance,
reports from Peshawar, Pakistan, said today.
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The British and Irish governments agreed today to
have former U.S. senator George Mitchell presiding over the
all-party talks in Northern Ireland next week.
</P>
<P>
KIEV -- Ukraine may re-consider the timetable for shutting down
the Chernobyl Nuclear Power Station because of delays by the G-7
group of industrialized countries in providing agreed-on funds of
three billion U.S. dollars, a senior government minister said
today.
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Chechen rebels today softened their hardline stance
on the withdrawal of Russian troops, saying they were ready to
conditionally accept Moscow's proposal to pull out in exchange for
simultaneous disarmament by the separatists.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Former U.S. Commerce Secretary Ron Brown was
killed in an accident caused by a deadly combination of factors
including questionable pilot decisions, U.S. Defense Secretary
William Perry said today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
