<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Serious" Ceasefire Violations Reported in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, June 7 (Xinhua) -- More than 10 "serious" ceasefire
violations in "all parts of the country" have been attributed to
the Revolutionary United Front (RUF) by the Sierra Leonean
security officials.
</P>
<P>
"We are being provoked and the aim is for us to violate the
ceasefire but we are holding back fire," a top security official
said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, the government called on the RUF over the
state radio "not only to uphold the spirit of the (yamasoukro)
meeting relating to the ceasefire but also to demonstrate respect
for the lives and property of Sierra Leoneans."
</P>
<P>
The statement, a second in three weeks by the government,
appealed to the international community to prevail on the RUF "to
desist from acts of violence against the civilian population and
dedicate itself to the cause of peace through negotiation."
</P>
<P>
According to west African diplomats, "the violations were more
intense in the south and east."
</P>
<P>
The statement did not say how many civilians have died so far
but local journalists put the figure at over 200 people, mainly
women and children.
</P>
<P>
RUF rebels are massing around the villages Yondo, Kpepoh and
Yangaesia in the Moyamba District in the south and that "the
whole town of Moyamba is now under siege," a local witness said.
</P>
<P>
"People are fleeing the area," he added.
</P>
<P>
Ten days ago, the government and the RUF ended nearly three
weeks of talks in the Ivorian city of Yamoussoukro after failing
to agree on two out of 28 points in the proposed agreement for
permanent peace in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile health authorities on Friday reacted for the first
time to the outbreak of lassa fever in the east saying that
"there is no cause for alarm'' and that the outbreak has been
"checked".
</P>
<P>
An "isolation ward" has been set up at the Kenema government
hospital for "effective case management and barrier nursing with
the cooperation of local health related non governmental
organizations," the health authorities said.
</P>
<P>
Since the outbreak of the disease in some west African
countries in April this year, more than 100 people have died with
dozens more hospitalized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
