<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> APEC Concludes Experts Meeting on Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Experts from all members of the
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) forum today ended their
two-day meeting on innovative approaches to environmentally
sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
At a press briefing after the meeting, Philippine Assistant
Environment Secretary Ramon Paje said the meeting was concluded
with six major recommendations, which will be submitted to the
APEC senior officials meeting on July 9 and 10 and the APEC
ministerial meeting on July 11 and 12 in Manila.
</P>
<P>
He said the recommendations include the introduction of
environment and natural resources accounting into the national
income accounts, utilization of market-based instruments in
addressing market failures and sharing of information and
expertise in promoting, adapting and adopting innovative
approaches to sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
The meeting on sustainable development was a Philippine
initiative introduced during the APEC leaders meeting in Osaka in
1995. The initiative aims to establish a collaborative framework
for creative financing as member economies face the growing
challenge of protecting the environment.
</P>
<P>
APEC groups Australia, Brunei, Canada, Chile, China, Hong Kong,
Indonesia, Japan, the Republic of Korea, Malaysia, Mexico, New
Zealand, Papua New Guinea, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand,
Chinese Taipei and the United States.
</P>
<P>
This year's APEC leaders meeting is scheduled for November in
Subic, the Philippines.  
</P>
</TEXT>
