<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 11:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Envisages Industrial Leap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 7 (xinhua) -- Egypt envisages a big leap forward
in its economy over the next 20 years, pledging to encourage
investment and upgrade technology.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State for Planning Zafer El-Beshri disclosed here
thursday that a national strategy for economic development has
been mapped out for the next two decades.
</P>
<P>
According to the local daily "The Egyptian Gazette" today,
Zafer told a gathering of the ruling National Democratic Party
that the new budget for the fiscal year 1996-1997 foresaw a 49
percent increase in investment.
</P>
<P>
The next few years will witness a considerable development in
the investment structure through implementing multifarious
scientific programs aiming to entice foreign investment, the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
Future budgets would focus on further increasing private sector
investments, with which 34 new industrial zones and some oil
projects would be established in the country, Zafer added.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the new industrial zones and oil projects
would cost about 3.8 billion Egyptian Pounds (about 1.1 billion
U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The minister stressed that the national banks should play an
important role in the development process, and will be given total
freedom to decide the exchange rate and profits.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Minister of Scientific Research Venice Kamel
Gouda has pointed to the need to adopt the latest technology.
</P>
<P>
"The ministry is exerting efforts to set up a productive base
built on modern science and national technology," she told a forum
here Thursday. She added that Egypt should be a technology
producer, not just importer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
