<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ten Foreign Scientists Become CAS Foreign Academicians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Charles Kao, T.Y. Lin and eight
other renowned foreign scientists who have made great
contributions to China's scientific undertaking were elected as
members of the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) today.
</P>
<P>
Their election came during the CAS eighth academicians'
conference that closed here today.
</P>
<P>
They come from Australia, Britain and the United States. They
are the second group of CAS foreign academicians. In June 1994,
Chen Ning Yang, Shiing-shen Chern, Tsung-Dao Lee, Joseph Needham
and ten other foreign scientists were elected as the first group
of CAS foreign academicians.
</P>
<P>
Among the foreign academicians elected today are British
metallurgical physicist Robert Cahn, American scientist C.W. Chu,
a pioneer in research into world high-temperature super-conductor,
American optics physicist Y.R. Shen, Charles Kao, an expert on
application of optical fibers and president of the Chinese
University of Hong Kong, American diamond expert H.K. Mao,
American testing rock expert P.J. Wyllie, American scientist
Y.W. Kan, a founder of DNA analysis and cell's special gene, and
American scientist T.Y. Lin, a world-famous expert on the civil
engineering structure.
</P>
<P>
Other foreign academicians include American materials scientist
A.Y. Cho, who has helped Chinese scientists advance research into
MBA, a theory essential to research into semi-conductors, metals
and insulating materials, and Australian astronomer
W.N. Christiansen, who has helped Chinese astronomers advance
research into astronomy for years and contributed to the
restoration of the seats of the Chinese Astronomical Society, the
Chinese Society of Electronics and the Chinese Association for
Science and Technology in relevant international organizations.
</P>
<P>
The CAS now has 24 foreign academicians.  Endiem
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
