<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hariri Urges Israel to Show Seriousness on Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
al-Hariri, in an exclusive interview with Xinhua here this
morning, urged the new Israeli government to show its seriousness
on the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the recent Israeli elections, Hariri said that
the new Israeli government should start to make "big efforts" to
convince the Arab and other countries with its seriousness on
peace and to avert a "prevailing impression that it is not
working for peace."
</P>
<P>
Benjamin Netanyahu, leader of the rightwing Israeli Likud
bloc, won a narrow victory in the May 29 national elections over
Shimon Peres, the incumbent Israeli prime minister and head of the
Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's success has raised doubt of Arab countries about
the resumption of the Arab-Israeli peace talks and prompted a
series of high-level Arab meetings, including a
Jordanian-Egyptian-Palestinian summit in Aqaba, Jordan, Wednesday
and another summit of Syria, Egypt and Saudi Arabia in Damascus
today.
</P>
<P>
"Until now, all what has been uttered by the Israeli
government is not encouraging, and is characterized with
negativity more than with positivity," Hariri said.
</P>
<P>
"However, the new Israeli government should start big efforts
to convince the public opinion, of both the Arabs and the world,
that it is serious on the subject of peace because there is a
prevailing impression that it is not working for peace," Hariri
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, being asked to form a new Israeli government in 45
days, is expected to seek participation of minor political and
religious parties since his Likud bloc won only 32 seats in the
120-seat parliament, two fewer than the Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
On the situations in the region in view of the results of the
Israeli elections, the Lebanese prime minister said, "Until now,
the things do not seem clear, and are overwhelmed by a negative
impression."
</P>
<P>
He clarified that the efforts which had been exerted by the
Lebanese government, particularly by the billionaire prime
minister himself, to attract more international contributions in a
proposed consultative committee was interrupted by the Israeli
elections, hoping that the efforts could be resumed soon.
</P>
<P>
"We are now waiting for the United States, the sponsor of the
peace process, to ask us to continue the negotiations regarding
the consultative committee and to set up the mechanism for its
execution," Hariri added.
</P>
<P>
The consultative committee, provided for in a cease-fire
understanding broked by the United States between Lebanon and
Israel in April, is aimed at drawing international aids for
repairing and rebuilding the infrastructure damaged in a 16-day
Israeli blitz in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In the Israeli large-scale military strikes in April, some 200
Lebanese were killed and four hundreds wounded, in addition to
damages up to 500 million dollars,
</P>
<P>
The consultative committee is also aimed at bringing more
foreign capital into Lebanon's ambitious reconstruction,
masterminded by Hariri, who took office in October 1992.
</P>
<P>
Touring Europe last month, the Lebanese prime minister
announced that his country needs 1 billion dollars per year in
the next five years to continue the reconstruction projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
