<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNHCR Faces Funding Crisis in Caucasus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- A funding crisis threatens to
disrupt UNHCR programs that directly assist some 250,000 refugees
and displaced people in Georgia and Azerbaijan and over 80,000
displaced people from Chechnya, the agency warned Friday.
</P>
<P>
The agency's Director for Europe John Horekens said that the UN
High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) now has financial reserves
of less than 10,000 U.S. dollars for its programs in Azerbaijan,
and less than 20,000 dollars for programs in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
The ongoing UNHCR emergency operation for displaced people
fleeing from Chechnya to other Russian republics has uncommitted
reserves of only 252,000 dollars, enough to cover operations only
through July, said Horekens.
</P>
<P>
"Unless significant contributions are made in support of these
activities, UNHCR will very soon be unable to commit any further
funds," he said, adding that the implications for the people
relying on aid could be "enormous."
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR's programs in the southern Caucasus focus on helping
these often desperately poor people to become more
self-reliant. It is running projects to improve the shelters of
these families and to increase their capacity to earn a living, by
providing seeds, tools and means to create small businesses.
</P>
<P>
"Failure to help will mean more uncertainty and despair, and
much less hope for the whole area," Horekens said.
</P>
<P>
The UNHCR has requested 16 million dollars to cover this year's
operations in Georgia and Azerbaijan. To date it has received only
5.3 million.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an appeal for 6.5 million dollars to cover the
UNHCR's 1996 programs to help people displaced from Chechnya has
so far yielded only 1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
"Our need is urgent. We could see non-governmental
organizations leaving this zone, because of the security
difficulties and because we can't promise them resources. That
would be disastrous," Horekens said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
