<HEADLINE> Ghana Sells National Telecom Stake in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Ghanaian government has decided
to sell 30 per cent of its stake in the National
Telecommunication Company, in a privatization bid aimed at
enhancing the service and improving the production of its
state-run enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Transport and Communications Edward Salia told the
latest issue of the West African Magzine that the plan is soon to
be announced by President Jerry Rawings of Ghana.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Ghanaian government already sold 50 percent of
its stake in the national gold-mining company which is the
largest in Africa.
</P>
<P>
These privatization bids aroused controvercy in the west
African country where some prople are of the view that the acts
are "unpatriotic".
</P>
<P>
Others think more active measures should be taken by the
government instead of just selling its shares to foreigners.
</P>
<P>
However, government officials said the measures taken by the
government are "effective" in a way that they could both raise
funds for national revenue and lead to better administration of
the poorly-run enterprises. 
</P>
