<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Public Discloses Misuse of Extra-budgetary Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- More than 400 calls from the public
have been made to a special 'dial a cheat' telephone hotline in
its first month of operation.
</P>
<P>
A further 100 people have written letters reporting cheats
who have misused extra-budgetary funds.
</P>
<P>
The calls and letters follow the decision by China's Ministry
of Finance to set up a special telephone hot-line on May 6 to target
the misuse of extra-budgetary funds.
</P>
<P>
China launched a national campaign to clean up and tighten
supervision of extra-budgetary funds in May. The ministry has said
that the campaign would last through September.
</P>
<P>
The calls and letters disclosed that some administrative and
law enforcement bodies have charged fees arbitrarily and imposed
fines irregularly, established funds not in line with regulations,
misused administrative fees, fines and confiscated money, the
ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The details provided by the public will enable the authorities
to track down cheats in the handling of extra-budgetary funds, the
ministry said, adding that the two provinces of Yunnan and
Heilongjiang have now opened telephone hot-lines of their own.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that extra-budgetary funds in China
have surged drastically since the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
Illegal and irregular activities have occurred in the use of
extra-budgetary funds partly due to lax management, said Jin
Lianshu, a senior official with the Central Commission for
Discipline Inspection of the Communist Party of China.
</P>
<P>
Jin noted that some extra-budgetary funds have been used to buy
luxury cars and houses, or to speculate in real estate and stocks,
and some of the funds have been embezzled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
