<HEADLINE> Largest Sino-Foreign Joint Fossil-Fueled Power Plant Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- A contract to build 3.22 million kw
fossil-fuelled generating units in east China's Shandong was
signed today in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The contract is for the largest Sino-foreign joint
fossil-fueled electricity-generating project, a joint effort of
the province's two companies, Hong Kong's China Light &AMP; Power
Company, and France's Electricite De France.
</P>
<P>
The project will cost 2.3 billion US dollars, with 1.03 billion
US dollars of which coming from Hong Kong and France.
</P>
<P>
Items of the project will include two 300,000 kw units for the
second phase of construction at Shiheng Power Plant, two 350,000
kw units for the second phase of construction at Heze Power Plant,
and two 660,000 kw units for the first phase of construction at
Liaocheng Power Plant.
</P>
<P>
All the items are expected to be completed by the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
During the 1996-2000 period, the province plans to add six
million to seven million installed capacity to meet the demands of
the local economic development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
