<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Science Conference Closes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- A five-day meeting of more than 800
members of the Chinese Academy of Sciences and the Chinese Academy
of Engineering ended today in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The conference elected CAS's new board of chairmen and 17
academicians of foreign nationalities, and awarded the Sixth Tan
Kah Kee Prize and the first Engineering Science Prize.
</P>
<P>
CAE President Zhu Guangya said at the closing ceremony that the
conference has been "rich in content" and "has achieved
anticipated effects".
</P>
<P>
During the conference, Zhu said, more than 160 academicians
made speeches, and academicians had heated discussions on the
national strategy of revitalizing the country with science and
education, the strategy of sustained development, the challenges
and opportunities before the science undertakings in China and the
future work for the two academies.
</P>
<P>
It has laid a foundation for the mapping out of the two
academies' Ninth Five-year Working Plan (1996-2000) and long-term
development plan, he said.
</P>
<P>
During the conference the two academies also jointly sponsored
scholarly report conferences, and 12 divisions organized separate
scholarly meetings and discussions.
</P>
<P>
At the closing ceremony ten scientists from the United States,
Britain, Australia and Hong Kong were elected as the second group of
CAS members of foreign nationalities, and seven engineering
technicians from the United States, Russia and Japan were elected
CAE's first foreign academicians.
</P>
<P>
The new CAS foreign members are Robert W. Cahn, Britain;
A.Y.Cho, USA; W.N. Christiansen, Australia; C.W.Chu, Y.W.Kan,
Charles K.Kao, T.Y.Lin, H.K.Mao, and Y.R.Shen, all from the USA;
and P.J.Wyllie from Britain.
</P>
<P>
Among the newly elected CAE academicians were Tingye Li,
Michel T. Halbouty, Ray W. Clough, Ieoh Ming Pei and Norman E
Borlaug of the United States, Tasuku Fuwa of Japan, and
G.S. Bushgens of Russia.
</P>
<P>
According to the charters of the two academies, they will
jointly sponsor the academicians' conference every two years
starting in 1996. The date is set for the first week of June in
even years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
