<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arms Talks for Former Yugoslavia Adjourned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Negotiators from Bosnia, Croatia,
the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia Friday failed to finalize an
arms reduction accord due to political differences, bypassing the
June 6 deadline.
</P>
<P>
Most of the major issues had been resolved in the last few days
but a couple of items need to be cleared, said Vigleik Eide, an
official of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe, which is mediating the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The talks involve representatives from Croatia, the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia comprising Serbia and Montenegro, the
Bosnian government, the Bosnian Muslim-Croat federation and the
Bosnian Serbs.
</P>
<P>
The June 6 deadline is set down in Article IV of the Dayton
peace agreement, reached last October to end four years of civil
war in the former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The Vienna talks seek to establish forces and weapons limits
within the former Yugoslavia to reduce the risk of a fresh
outbreak of war in the Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
The differences focused on how the individual parties were to be
referred to in the text of an agreement, Eide, a former Norwegian
general, told reporters early this morning in Vienna's former
imperial Hofburg palace.
</P>
<P>
The Muslim-led Bosnian government opposed referring to
Bosnian Serb territory as "Republika Srpska" for fear that Serbs
may present their territory as a separate state instead of part of
Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
Some negotiators insisted that Croatia, Bosnia and the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia initial the agreement as separate nations
while the Muslim-Croat Confederation and the Bosnian Serbs initial
the agreement as two regions of Bosnia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
