<HEADLINE> Nepalese Leaders Stress Economic Ties with China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Nepal sees broad prospects for
economic relations with China in the fields of energy,
infrastructure and tourism, Nepalese Prime Minister Sher Bahadur
Deuba said here today.
</P>
<P>
Deuba, who visited China last April, told a visiting group of
Chinese journalists that he had been deeply impressed with China's
rapid economic growth.
</P>
<P>
"My government would make an effort to introduce China's
experience to Nepal," he said.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with the delegation from the Xinhua News Agency
headed by its vice-president Gao Qiufu, Deuba said social
stability is the first priority for his coalition government while
"economic development comes next."
</P>
<P>
Deuba's views were shared by Foreign Minister Prakash Chandra
Lohani at another meeting with the delegation today.
</P>
<P>
Lohani said Nepal and China have agreed to organize annual
people-people forums with the participation of business people,
academics and government representatives, which are scheduled to
start in September.
</P>
<P>
"I place high hopes on the forums," he said.
</P>
<P>
Lohani noted that the economies of Nepal and China are
complementary in many ways, adding that the governments "should
encourage their contacts, which would lead to mutual
understanding, trust and investment."
</P>
<P>
He said Nepal is keen on absorbing China's investment and
technology.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the issue of human rights, Lohani said China's
rapid economic growth has resulted in higher living standards and
greater employment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
"These are the fundamentals of human rights. This is also
China's outstanding contribution to world peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Xinhua delegation is visiting this Himalayan kingdom at the
invitation of Nepal's official news agency RSS.  
</P>
