<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Award for Scientists Given </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Eight Chinese scientists who have
made significant contributions to the country's development in
science and technology received a top prize today.
</P>
<P>
As winners of the '95 Tan Kah Kee Prize, each of the scientists
received a medal and 100,000 yuan (over 12,000 U.S. dollars) at a
prize-rewarding ceremony held before the closing of the five-day
national academicians' conference in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Ye Duzheng, one of the winners, is the founder of China's
modern aerology. His discovery about the sudden changes of general
circulation, the first ever in the world, contributed much to
China's summer weather forecasting. Ye was also the first
scientist in the world who found out that Qinghai-Tibetan Plateau,
located in western part of China, influences the climate, weather
and environment of the northern hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
Yang Jiachi, an expert of space automatic control, was one of
the heroes who developed China's guided missile and atomic bomb in
1960s, as well as launching recoverable satellites successfully
several times.
</P>
<P>
This is the sixth time that Tan Kah Kee Prize has been
granted. The Prize, regarded as one of the top awards for Chinese
scientists, was established in 1988 with donations from offspring
of Tan Kah Kee, an overseas Chinese who had built schools and
colleges in China during his life time.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
