<HEADLINE> Karpov Takes Opening Game of World Chess Match </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Anatoly Karpov claimed the opening
game of the 20-game world chess series Friday against Gata Kamsky,
didn't resume the adjourned game in Elista, Russia.
</P>
<P>
Both players adjourned for the night late Thursday after 56
moves. Kamsky conceded defeat one hour before the scheduled
resumption of play Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Kamsky will play white in the second game Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Karpov held the undisputed world crown for a decade
until Garry Kasparov replaced him in 1985. He now is defending his
World Chess Federation title in the capital of the southern
Russian republic of Kalmykia.
</P>
<P>
Kamsky, a Russian emigre who now lives in New York City, won
the U.S. title at age 16 and was raised by his iron-willed father.
</P>
<P>
Rustam Kamsky, his volatile father and coach, caused a stir on
the eve of the match, engaging in a shouting match with Karpov's
aides in last-minute haggling over the rules.
</P>
<P>
The dispute ended Thursday in Karpov's favor, when chess
federation president Kirsan Ilyumzhinov agreed to allow play to be
adjourned after 56 moves. The previous agreement had limited play
to seven hours with no adjournment.
</P>
<P>
Games will be played every other day until one player reaches
10.5 points. Victories are worth a point, draws a half-point.
</P>
</TEXT>
