<HEADLINE> Seven Foreign Scientists Become CAE Academicians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- World-renowned Chinese-American
architect Ieoh Ming Pei and six other foreign scientists and
experts, today became the first group of foreign academicians to
be honored by the Chinese Academy of Engineering (CAE).
</P>
<P>
The seven people have made outstanding contributions to China's
modernization process.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made at the closing ceremony of the joint
academicians conference of the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS)
and the CAE.
</P>
<P>
Ieoh Ming Pei, 79, is one of the world's leading architects. He
has made important suggestions for drafting a urban development
plan for Beijing, and also designed the Beijing Xiangshan
(Fragrant Hill) Hotel.
</P>
<P>
G.S. Bushgens, a 79-year-old Russian expert on aerodynamics,
aided China in designing supersonic attackers in the 1960s, helped
China design new varieties of planes in the 1990s, and trained
more than 250 Chinese experts on aircraft design.
</P>
<P>
Tingye Li, 65, a Chinese-American fiber-optics communications
expert with AT&AMP;T, introduced a number of famous U.S. scientists
who will lecture in China, and offered several proposals for the
development of China's fiber-optics communications.
</P>
<P>
Tasuku Fuwa, 81, a Japanese export on metallurgical physics,
aided China in its efforts to improve techniques used in iron and
steel making, and trained a number of engineers and technicians in
that field.
</P>
<P>
Michel T. Halbouty, 85, a U.S. oil geologist, is CAE's oldest
foreign academician. He was the first scientist to suggest oil
prospecting be done in northeast China's Tarim Basin.
</P>
<P>
Ray W. Clough, 74, a U.S. seismic engineer, helped solve
difficult anti-seismic problems that surfaced during the building
of arch dams at the Ertan Hydropower Station, an important State
construction project.
</P>
<P>
The American expert has also contributed to China's development
of anti-seismic technology used in building arch dams.
</P>
<P>
Norman E. Borlaug, 82, a top-level U.S. grain breeder and Nobel
Peace Prize-winner, greatly aided China's research on the
promotion of wheat and maize production.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
