<HEADLINE> HK Airline Collects Change to Help Needy Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Cathay Pacific, the leading
airline in Hong Kong, has launched an annual fund-raising program
to collect spare change from passengers to help needy children
around the world.
</P>
<P>
The program, titled "Change for Good," will be carried out on
all Cathay Pacific flights between June 1 and October 31 this
year. Each passenger will receive an envelope in which they can
donate their spare foreign change.
</P>
<P>
Money raised will be donated to the United Nations Children's
Fund to help children in 141 developing, war-torn or
disaster-stricken countries.
</P>
<P>
Cathay Pacific operates an average of 150 international flights
 a day, carrying nearly 30,000 passengers. The airline has pooled
1.5 million US dollars worth of foreign change since it initiated
the campaign in 1991.
</P>
<P>
According to the United Nations, one US dollar can afford
enough high-dose vitamin A capsules to save a kid from trachoma
and eye disease, while 3.85 US dollars can provide 100 capsules of
 an antibiotic to treat serious infections.  
</P>
</TEXT>
