<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier on Reform of State-owned Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Local officials in Zhejiang
province, east China, have been urged to become trailblazers to
give the country's state-owned enterprises an end-of-century boost.
</P>
<P>
They were told to emancipate their minds to start bold
experiments to step up the reforms of state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
During a three-day inspection tour, which ended today,
Vice-Premier Wu Bangguo said since China has clearly defined its
orientation, basic principles and policies towards reform of
state-owned enterprises, local officials should work hard to
promote the changes in economic structure and growth mode to
increase economic returns, by blazing new trails for reform and
development of state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Accompanied by provincial officials, Wu, also a member of the
Political Bureau of the Communist Party Central Committee, visited
a number of enterprises in Zhejiang and listened to work reports
by local governments.
</P>
<P>
In discussions he urged local officials to integrate reform,
transformation, reorganization of management to invigorate the
larger enterprises, and setting smaller enterprises free.
</P>
<P>
He called on the province to adhere to public ownership as the
main force, while giving due attention to the development of
diversified economic entities.
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier urged local officials to promote experiments
in establishing modern enterprise systems, and improving capital
structures with emphasis to supporting the 1,000 leading
enterprises, particularly the capitals used in production of the
300 state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
To do the current work well in the industrial sphere, China
should stress market surveys and predictions, promotion of
technical advances, and marketing with special support for
enterprises with good economic performances, high export volumes
and with high selling products, Wu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
