<HEADLINE> 22 Places Declared Red Tide Calamity in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
today declared a state of calamity in 22 cities and municipalities
in the Manila Bay area, which have been affected by the red tide
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
Ramos also approved the release of 100,000 pesos (4,000 US
dollars) to each of these places from the Calamity Fund as
national aid to the local government units in providing assistance
to victims as well as affected or dislocated fishermen and their
families.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary Renato de Villa, who recommended the
declaration of calamity in the 22 places, reported that tests
conducted by a red tide task force showed a high toxicity level on
seashells and mussels gathered in these areas.
</P>
<P>
The task force, he said, has already issued a total ban on the
harvest, sale, transport and consumption of shellfish in the
entire Manila Bay area.
</P>
<P>
At least three Filipinos died and 48 others are hospitalized
after eating mussels affected by the red tide.  
</P>
</TEXT>
