<HEADLINE> A Hong Kong Man Convicted Forging Credit Cards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 6 (Xinhua) -- A Hong Kong resident, Xiao
Yaowen, was today sentenced to seven years in prison for forging
securities in Guangzhou, capital of south China's Guangdong
province.
</P>
<P>
The Guangzhou Intermediate People's Court said that Xiao's
deeds had severely impaired the financial management and the order
of credit cards.
</P>
<P>
Xiao was once arrested in Hong Kong for defrauding property. In
August 1993, he fled to Shenzhen in Guangdong province while on
bail.
</P>
<P>
In 1994 he set up a workshop in his temporary apartment in
Shenzhen to produce forged credit cards with a Hong Kong resident
called "Allen".
</P>
<P>
Allen provided equipment and raw materials for him to forge
cards. From September to November 1994, Xiao forged more than 200
credit cards. Some of the cards were carried to Hong Kong by Allen.
</P>
<P>
Policemen arrested Xiao in Shenzhen on November 17, 1994, and
found 99 forged cards and a batch of equipment for forging cards
in his possession in his apartment.
</P>
<P>
After the pronouncement of judgement, Xiao said he will lodge
an appeal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
