<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Mural Paintings Feature Nepali Petroleum Pools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Chinese experts have solved the
puzzle of flaming pools of water, found in ancient murals.
</P>
<P>
They have proved that the fire water was caused by burning
petrol.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese ancient mural paintings show that Nepal had an
abundance of petroleum resources in ancient times, according to
the findings of a Chinese archaeologist.
</P>
<P>
Chinese archaeologists discovered a long time ago that a dozen
of ancient mural paintings, which date back to the Tang (618-907)
and Song (960-1127) Dynasties, featured mysterious water pools in
flames.
</P>
<P>
The paintings were found in the Dunhuang and Yulin Grottos in
northwest China's Gansu and Shaanxi Provinces. Both are famous for
rich collections of ancient Buddhist arts.
</P>
<P>
However, it was always a riddle whether the "burning pools" in
the paintings were ancient realities or pure imagination of
religious people.
</P>
<P>
Sun Xiushen, a veteran researcher at the Dunhuang Institute of
Gansu, has now claimed that after years of studies on the
paintings and historical records, he has the answer.
</P>
<P>
"These mural paintings are scientific records of the discovery
of petroleum in ancient Nepal, though some mythical elements of
Buddhism were added," he said. "The 'burning pools' are in fact
the Nepali petroleum pools."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that according to historical books, China and
Nepal started political, economic, and cultural exchanges some
1,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Many Chinese travellers, including Xuan Zhuang, a Buddhist monk
in Tang Dynasty who went to India to study Buddhism by way of
Nepal, left records of the "burning pools" in Nepal in their
journals, he added.
</P>
<P>
One of them described: "the pools are tens of Zhang (some 3
meters) wide, and will catch fire if a single spark falls in; the
flames will not be extinguished, but only fuelled, by pouring
water..."
</P>
<P>
With these vivid accounts, he said, the Nepali petroleum pools
were gradually known to the ancient Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
"When artists started to work on the Dunhuang Grottos in mid
Tang Dynasty, they featured these pools in their paintings as part
of the Buddhist arts," he speculated.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0138 </DOCNO>
