<HEADLINE> 82 Killed in Yunnan Landslide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- A total of 82 people are believed
to have been killed and another 77 injured in the two major
landslides in Southwest China's Yunnan Province.
</P>
<P>
Three major mine entrances remain to be opened, making it
difficult to rescue people who may be still alive in the
mines. Local sources report that 144 people are missing.
</P>
<P>
The landslides, occurred on May 31 and June 3 in Laojinshan
Mountain, site of the Daping Cold Mine in Yuanyang County
following non-stop torrential rain.
</P>
<P>
As more heavy rain followed in the past few days new landslides
are possible. The deformed mountains and thick soil from the
landslides makes it harder to locate the mines and for rescue
work, said a local official.
</P>
<P>
At present up to a thousand rescue workers are digging the mine
entraces and the State Council, China's highest governing body,
has sent a working group to Yunnan to help with the rescue
work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
