<HEADLINE> Over 600 Criminals Surrender to Police in Shangdong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Over 600 criminals have surrendered
themselves to police voluntarily in east China's Shandong Province
since a national anti-crime campaign was launched on April 28.
</P>
<P>
To date various departments in the province have distributed
more than 3.6 million pamphlets and convened numerous meetings,
attended by relatives of criminals at large, in a move to persuade
more criminals to surrender themselves to police.
</P>
<P>
As China pursues a policy of generosity to the frank, severity
to the risisting, and awards to those who render meritorious
service, more criminals seem want to surrender, a senior official
concerned with the province said.
</P>
<P>
Having been at large ever since he raped a girl in Yuantai
County, Shandong Province, in 1993, Zhu Qingqiang surrendered
himself to police on May 7, accompanied by his father, saying that
"it's not a good solution to be at large for all of one's life. "
</P>
