<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean Traverses Sahara Desert on Foot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 7 (Xinhua) -- He conquered the 8,848-meter-high
Mount Qomolangma (Mt. Everest), the world's highest peak, in
1987. He reached the North Pole in 1991. Now he has become the
first person in the world to take a west-to-east route to traverse
the Sahara Desert on foot.
</P>
<P>
Choi Jong-Ryul, a 38-year-old adventurer from the Republic of
Korea, overcame a series of hellish challenges, including vast
stretches of sand with high dunes, scorching sunlight, quicksand,
blinding sandstorms, scorpions, poisonous insects and a lack of
water, to complete his seven-month trek in Suakin, Sudan, Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Choi, who set out in Nouakchott, Mauritania, on November 11,
1995, was supported on the journey by three other South Koreans
who drove two jeeps provided by South Korea's Kia Motors Corp.,
one of the two sponsors of the expedition. But the vehicles were
not always with him, Choi said.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held in Cairo Thursday, Choi, pointing to
a map, said that he and the vehicles actually took two different
routes, but at certain places they joined together with Choi
receiving supplies from his three compatriots traversing the
world's largest desert by car. They kept in contact through a
walkie-talkie, he said.
</P>
<P>
Oh Kang-Suk, a journalist of the South Korean leading newspaper
Dong-A llbo (East Asia Daily) which was the other sponsor of the
expedition, Lee Tae-Sun and Lee Jong-Lae were also considered
heros by finishing the journey from Nouakchott to Suakin, though
most of the time in vehicles. They occasionally accompanied Choi
to walk.
</P>
<P>
Choi, who covered some 7,400 kilometers, and the three arrived
on June 4 in Suakin, a Sudanese Red Sea port.
</P>
<P>
Choi told reporters that he suffered diarrhea twice on the
journey and wore through seven pairs of shoes.
</P>
<P>
"Every day I woke up at 4:30 in the morning, then had my
breakfast for 30 minutes and started walking at five o'clock," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He walked for 13 hours a day, stopping only for an hour to cook
and eat a simple meal of rice, dried beef and pork, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said he covered five kilometers per hour on the average,
describing his journey in Mauritania as the most difficult part of
his trek.
</P>
<P>
"At the beginning I walked about 40 kilometers per day, and
four months later I began to cover 60 kilometers a day," he said
through an interpreter from Kia Motors Corp..
</P>
<P>
Asked what motivated him to make such a feat, Choi said, "I
just wanted to know how a person reacted in extremely bad
conditions."
</P>
<P>
For such a rigorous journey, it took him two years to prepare,
including the eight months spent on looking for a sponsor.
</P>
<P>
"The (Sahara) desert is more beautiful than I expected," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the people he met on his journey were very
friendly to him, but he had to communicate with them by making
gestures because of language problems.
</P>
<P>
The trek had been scheduled to end on May 28, 1996 at el-Quesir
in Egypt. However, due to the closure of the border between Sudan
and Egypt, the destination was changed to Suakin.
</P>
<P>
Choi, who will return to Seoul, South Korea Sunday, said that
he would try some other adventures in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
