<HEADLINE> Latvia, China Sign Two Cooperation Accords </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIGA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Latvia and China signed two agreements
here today on cooperation in science and technology and avoidance
of double taxation and prevention of tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
The documents were signed after talks between Chinese Vice
Premier Li Lanqing and his Latvian counterpart, Ziedonis Cevers.
</P>
<P>
Cevers said his country welcomes Chinese investment and hopes
for more joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
He also offered China use of Latvian sea ports and other
facilities to transport its goods to a third country.
</P>
<P>
Li promised that China will take steps to expand trade
with Latvia.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese government attaches importance to economic
and technological cooperation and would encourage prestigious
Chinese enterprises to invest and set up joint ventures in the
Baltic country.
</P>
<P>
Cevers said he hoped the two countries, which have no
differences in political views, will maintain and push forward
their good relations.
</P>
<P>
Li said China respects Latvia's independence and sovereignty
and understands Latvia's hope for membership of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
He said China, as a permanent member of the United Nations
Security Council, is concerned not only with security and
stability in Asia, but also with European security and stability.
</P>
<P>
China hopes that Europe will set up as soon as possible a
security structure that will address the interests of all the
countries concerned, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese vice-premier also met today with Saeima
(parliament) deputy chairman, Alfred Chepanis.
</P>
<P>
Li said the Chinese government is grateful to the Latvian
government and parliament for their one-China stance and supports
contacts and cooperation between the two legislatures.
</P>
<P>
Latvia is the final leg of Li's five-nation European tour.
Before arriving in Riga Thursday, he visited Hungary, Poland,
Lithuania and Estonia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
