<HEADLINE> Chinese-Polish Shipping Company Celebrates 45th Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese-Polish Joint Stock
Shipping Company, thought to be the oldest Sino-foreign joint
venture in New China, celebrated its 45th birthday today in
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Among the guests attending a celebration meeting were Huang
Zhendong, Chinese Minister of Communications; Boguslzawl
Liberadzki, Polish minister of Maritime Economy and
Transportation; Xia Keqiang, vice mayor of Shanghai; and Zdzislaw
Goralczyk, Polish ambassador to China.
</P>
<P>
Founded in June, 1951 by the Chinese and Polish governments,
CPJSC by the end of last year had handled cargo transportation
amounting to 35.4 million tons and a turnover of 373.75 billion
nautical mile/ton.
</P>
<P>
At present the company owns a fleet of 21 multi-functional
goods carriers and container ships with a total capacity of
420,000 DWTs. Three new ships of 22,000 tons ordered by the
company are still being built.
</P>
<P>
An operator of regular liners linking China with Western
Europe, Mediterranean and Southeast Asian countries, the company
has made important contributions to Sino-Polish trade, and trade
with other countries. Apart from ocean-going transport it also
developed industries worth over 40 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The achievements of the company once won praise from Chinese
Premier Li Peng who said that the company "has written a glorious
chapter on the history of friendship and cooperation of the
Chinese and Polish peoples". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
