<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Draft of Guidelines Formulated for New Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The guidelines of the soon-to-be-
formed new Israeli government have been formulated and the Hebrew
newspaper Maariv published a draft text today.
</P>
<P>
According to Israel Media Digest, prominent in these guidelines
are three "noes" -- no to a Palestinian state, no to a dividing
of Jerusalem, and no to concessions on the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
The guidelines also state, "The settlement operation in all
parts of the land is an expression of our right over the land,
and it constitutes an integral part of our national security. the
government will guarantee the continued existence and development
of the new settlement, and will allocate for this purpose the
required resources."
</P>
<P>
The Oslo agreements are not mentioned in the draft, but one of
the clauses states that "the government will conduct negotiations
with the Palestinian Authority to achieve a permanent peace
agreement, while strictly maintaining Israel's security needs,
including a materializing of the Palestinian commitment to
prevent terror, to extradite murderers, and not to incite against
Israel."
</P>
<P>
The guidelines include furthering relations with Egypt and
Jordan and raising level of diplomatic relations with other Arab
countries.
</P>
<P>
As for Jerusalem, the draft document calls for additional
funding for the city in order to expand housing and municipal
services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
