<HEADLINE> Monks Win Lawsuit Against Ham Manufacturer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, June 7 (Xinhua) -- A sausage ham manufacturer in
central China has lost a two-year lawsuit for misusing the image
of a monk in ham advertising.
</P>
<P>
Zhengzhou Intermediate People's Court has announced that the
Luohe Canned Food Factory have to apologize and compensate 5,000
yuan to Shaolin Temple, located near Zhengzhou, capital of Henan
Province, the Guangzhou-based "Yangcheng Evening News" reported.
</P>
<P>
The factory asked an advertising company to produce a TV
commercial for its "Shaolin" brand sausage ham in September,
1993. The production showed images of Shaolin monks playing
martial arts and, then, different kinds of ham products, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The advertising also claimed that the products were as famous
as "Shaolin" kung fu, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Monks of Shaolin Temple showed strong resentment shortly after
the commercial was broadcast on China Central TV, which covers the
whole country, and local Henan TV.
</P>
<P>
They urged the TV stations to stop the broadcast and sued the
factory for violation of Shaolin's fame, because the advertising
related a meat product with the vegetarian Buddhist temple.
</P>
<P>
Shaolin Temple is one of the most famous Buddhist temples in
China for its martial arts, and is also a hot tourist
attraction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
