<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Improve Use of Water Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, June 7 (Xinhua) -- China wastes more than 10 billion
cubic meters of water a year, a major conservancy conference was
told in Tianjin today.
</P>
<P>
Now top officials have called for more effort to be placed
into developing the country's comprehensive use of water
resources, lifting its utilization ratio and economic returns, to
combat the country's waste.
</P>
<P>
This was set forth at a five-day national economic working
conference on water conservancy which ended today in Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
An important resource for humans, water is closely linked with
the people's living standards, economic development and social
progress.
</P>
<P>
Officials at the meeting pointed out that China is short of
water, while facing serious water wastages. Recycled utilization
ratio of water for industrial use only reaches 30 percent or so,
and utilization coefficient of water for agricultural irrigation
works out at 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
In order to develop the country's water resources, China will
set up economic belts along seven valleys of the Yangtze River,
Yellow River, Pearl River, Haihe River and other rivers.
</P>
<P>
The country will also import more overseas investment to
further increase international co-operation to improve economic
returns in the sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Expects to Put out Fire in Major Coal Fields </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- China's highest governing body, the
State Council, has approved the setting aside of 86 million yuan
(about 10.4 million US dollars) to put out fires in two major coal
fields in the northwest of the country.
</P>
<P>
Fires in Xiaolongkou and Xiaohuangshan coal fields in Fukang
County, Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, are expected to be
extinguished by 1999, China Geology and Mineral Resources News has
reported.
</P>
<P>
The 432-square-meter fire area in the two fields burn 24.68
million tons of coal annually, equivalent to Xinjiang's total coal
output for one year. They are the last two major coal fields that
are still on fire in Xinjiang.
</P>
<P>
So far fires in six coal fields have been put out, three of
which are state-set major coal fields.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang's coal reserves rank first in China, but fire
disasters are also serious. At present a total of 102 square
kilometers in 42 coal fields are on fire in Xinjiang.
</P>
<P>
Fires have eaten up 100 million tons annually, the report said,
adding that up to now, 2.1 billion tons of quality coal have been
burned to ashes.
</P>
<P>
China has been busy with putting out fires in Xinjiang's coal
fields for 38 years, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Container Shipping Flourishing on Yangtze River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Booming economy and trade along
the Yangtze River has boosted container shipping along the longest
river in China.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are 11 container transport routes in service
between Shanghai and other river cities. In the first five months
of this year, monthly transport volume on these routes averaged
21,000 TEUs, double the monthly figure recorded last year.
</P>
<P>
This soaring transport business on the Yangtze has attracted 80
percent of China's international liner companies to establish more
than 120 agent offices along the river for international cargo.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the General Administration of Customs of China
approved the formation of customs offices on all the ports along
the Yangtze, which further facilitated the container transport
service.
</P>
<P>
A port construction drive is now in full swing along the river
to cope with the growing transport business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
