<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Sets Up Fuel Storage Facilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Underground storage facilities
capable of holding a six-month supply of Zimbabwe's needs of
petrol, diesel and jet-a1 fuels were commissioned yesterday by
President Robert Mugabe in southeast Harare.
</P>
<P>
Built by the Swedish construction company Skanska, the Mabvuku
underground complex has cost at least 50 million U.S.
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The complex comprises a service area where non-flammable
substances and utility equipment is kept and a hazardous zone
where the fuel lines run through.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the official opening, President Mugabe said fuel
was an important resource in the development of the country and
it was vital for sound storage systems to be put in place taking
into consideration that Zimbabwe is landlocked.
</P>
<P>
He said the facility would also enhance regional cooperation
in that Zimbabwe would be able to come to the rescue of needy
states in southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe has exported fuel products to Malawi, Zaire and
Botswana. 
</P>
