<HEADLINE> Africa's Debt Unpayable, Says Mkapa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President Benjamin
Mkapa has said that Africa's debt was unpayable and appealed
creditor nations and institutions to write-off or reschedule it,
local reports said today.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa was quoted as telling an international conference
of the congregation of missionary benedictine sisters of tutzig
here on Thursday that the debt burden was "a millstone around
the neck of Africa".
</P>
<P>
He told the conference sub-Saharan Africa's external debt rose
from 84.3 billion US dollars in 1980 to a staggering 313 billion
dollars in 1994.
</P>
<P>
President Mkapa said Tanzania's debt stood at more than seven
billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
"If we were to apportion this debt to every man, woman and
child, each one of them would be indebted to the magnitude of
their total incomes for two and half years", he explained.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said Tanzania spent 2,425 million dollars last financial
year to service the national debt, an amount he said was sufficient
to meet the budgeted expenditure of seven major government
ministries. enditem

