<HEADLINE> IMF Predicts Investment Boom in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 7 (Xinhua)-- Uganda is expected to witness an
investment boom after the presidential elections held last May,
reported the local newspaper the Monitor today.
</P>
<P>
Ulrike Wilson, Resident Representative of the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) here, was quoted as saying, "An investment
boom is also expected after the elections."
</P>
<P>
Wilson announced that Uganda had been confirmed as one of the
countries to benefit from the multilateral debt relief program.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's debt burden stands at about 3.5 billion US Dollars.
</P>
<P>
She disclosed that a final decision on the matter would
probably be taken at the financial body's annual meeting next
October.
</P>
<P>
She also disclosed that uganda could qualify for higher aid
from the IMF Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility.
</P>
<P>
She attributed Uganda's confirmation to the continued
outstanding economic and financial performance in the present
fiscal year. 
</P>
