<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Coalition Talks Stalled over Tough </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Talks on forming Israel's new
coalition government have been stalled over tough demands of the
religious parties who want to reverse the religious status quo to
that before 1992.
</P>
<P>
Negotiators from the Likud bloc and the religious parties
adjourned their talks Thursday without reaching any
agreement. They only agreed to resume the talks Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Their troubles include difference in coalition guidelines,
portfolio demands and the bickering among the religious parties
over the Religious Affairs portfolio, and increasing unrest within
Likud itself.
</P>
<P>
However, Prime Minister-elect Benjamin Netanyahu was still
optimistic regarding his plan to form a coalition by June 17,
when the new Knesset (parliament) convenes for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu expected the religious parties to be more realistic
in making their demands, aides close to him said.
</P>
<P>
Likud sources said that Likud's negotiators were quite
stunned by the tough demands presented by the religious
parties which include Shas, The National Religious Party (NRP)
and United Torah Judaism (UTJ).
</P>
<P>
The religious parties' demands include:
</P>
<P>
-- Reversing the status quo on religious affairs to that before
Labor took over power in 1992;
</P>
<P>
-- Making recognition of all conversions conditional on
approval by the Chief Rabbinate;
</P>
<P>
-- Enacting a basic law guaranteeing the Jewish character of
the state; and
</P>
<P>
-- Ensuring there would be no legislative initiative or adding
new coalition partners without the consent of all members of the
original coalition.
</P>
<P>
They argued a reversal of the religious status quo is
necessary because the Labor-Meretz government has altered it
since 1992.
</P>
<P>
The last demand is seen as an attempt by the religious parties
to win veto power on admitting Labor into the coalition, which
the Likud might consider in order to limit the power of its
smaller coalition partners.
</P>
<P>
Likud negotiators replied that the religious parties must
tone down their aspirations and refrain from pressing on with
unrealistic demands, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
As for the portfolio allocation, Likud and the religious camp
remain divided.
</P>
<P>
As both the NRP and Shas demanded to take the Religious Affairs
portfolio, Likud suggested a third choice. The NRP threatened not
to join the coalition if it is not awarded the post.
</P>
<P>
The Likud offered the NRP the Education and Communications
portfolios, but it wanted the Labor and Social Affairs posts,
which had been allocated to Shas together with the Interior
portfolio. The UTJ was offered the Housing post and the
chairmanship of Knesset's Finance Committee.
</P>
<P>
Likud sources said Netanyahu plans to keep many powerful
departments under his control, a move set to upset future
ministers. These include control over both TV channels and
cable TV, the Finance Ministry's budget division, and the
Israeli Lands Administration.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, tension is brewing within the Likud-Gesher-Tsomet
faction, as Netanyahu continues to fray the nerves of his
party colleagues and campaigning partners.
</P>
<P>
While Gesher's leader David Levy is expected to take over
the Foreign Affairs portfolio, Tsomet's head Rafael Eitan, who
eyes the Defense or Housing post, was unhappy with Netanyahu's
silence.
</P>
<P>
To ease the tension, Netanyahu decided to meet Likud's
veteran Ariel Sharon next week for the first time since the
elections to discuss the portfolio allocation. Sharon is aiming
for the Finance or Housing portfolio.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu is heavily indebted to Sharon, hardline former
Defense Minister, for his role in forming the Likud-Gesher-Tsomet
faction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
