<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Asks Schools to Stop Making Money from Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Schools should stop collecting
excessive fees from students and their families, urged a
government circular here today.
</P>
<P>
The notice, issued by the State Council's General Office, said
that some elementary and secondary schools are charging students a
large sum of "unreasonable money" and even are demanding expensive
gifts from them.
</P>
<P>
"That has added burden to the students and their families," the
notice said.
</P>
<P>
Some township and rural governments have solicited money from
farmers in the name of building schools, which has affected
farmers' living standards.
</P>
<P>
Some schools forced their students to buy insurance, the notice
added.
</P>
<P>
It urged governments at various levels to increase educational
investments, build enough schools, and gradually exempt childrens'
school fees.
</P>
<P>
China is adopting a nine-year-compulsory education system,
which means elementary and secondary school students need not pay
tuition fees, and the country's education law stipulates that any
school cannot pursue profit.
</P>
<P>
But some schools have been collecting excessive sums of money
from students due to a lack of educational funding.
</P>
<P>
China has nearly one million elementary and secondary schools
with about 200 million students.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
