<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Calls U.S. Reaction on OAS's Resolution "Hysterical" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Cuba today described as "hysterical"
the U.S.'s reaction to this week's resolution by the Organization
of American States (OAS) condemning the tightened U.S. economic
embargo against the Caribbean island.
</P>
<P>
Cuban Foreign Ministry spokesman Miguel Alfonso also accused
the U.S. administration of trying to ignore the 1964 U.S. Supreme
Court ruling which recognizes the right of the Cuban government to
nationalize foreigners' property.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has objected to a resolution passed on Tuesday at the
OAS annual meeting rejecting the so-called Helms-Burton law,
passed by Congress in March punishing U.S. and overseas companies
which do business in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The OAS general assembly asked the Interamerican Juridical
Committee to give its opinion on the validity of the Helms-Burton
Law.
</P>
<P>
But U.S. State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns announced
that Washington does not recognize the jurisdiction of the IJC.
</P>
<P>
He also described as theft the nationalization of foreign
enterprises in Cuba after Fidel Castro seized power in 1958.
</P>
</TEXT>
