<HEADLINE> Cyprus to Further Control Illegal Foreign Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The Cyprus government will table a
bill before the new House of Representatives providing for
stricter measures against those who illegally employ foreign
workers.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that some 12,000 foreign workers are currently
employed on this East Mediterranean island without the necessary
permits, in addition to another 10,000 who are legally employed,
according to the local press today.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Dinos Michaelides said this week that the
government will adopt a strong policy against those who illegally
employ foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
The three-year prison sentences provided for under the
proposed law are expected to act as a deterrent to employers
violating immigration and labor regulations, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
"Once this policy becomes known, foreign workers will not come
to Cyprus with the intention of illegally seeking employment," he
said, adding that he hoped the bill would be passed into law by
the new House in September when it reconvenes after the summer
recess.
</P>
<P>
There have been numerous complaints and demonstrations against
the employment of foreigners, with hotel workers in particular
claiming that many of them are jobless while foreign workers
without work permits are being employed on low wages, and thus
undermining the local labor market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
