<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Game Adjourned Between Karpov and Kamsky </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Chess world champion Anatoly Karpov
of Russia enjoyed the upperhands as the first of the 20-game
series World Championship was adjourned after 56 moves on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In Elista, Kalmyk Republic, Karpov, 45, opened the game with a
d4 pawn, and American challenger Gata Kamsky, 22, responded with
the Grunfeld defense.
</P>
<P>
Under the rule, each player should make 40 moves in the first
two hours and 16 more moves in another 60 minutes.
</P>
<P>
And the game will be adjourned as neither of them conquers the
other after the first 56 moves.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the end of the game, both players were left with a
rook, a bishop, a knight and three pawns each, with Karpov in a
clear advantage as his pawns were spread in dangerous spots.
</P>
<P>
The game is scheduled to resume on Friday, and the first who
scores 10.5 points will become the new world champion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
