<HEADLINE> Cuba to Attract Foreign Investment to Tax-Free Zones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Cuba will set up tax-free industrial
parks and commercial areas to offer new opportunities to foreign
investment and generate more jobs.
</P>
<P>
Cuban Foreign Investment and Collaboration Minister Ibrahim
Ferradaz told a press conference today that the decision was made
by the Council of the State Monday.
</P>
<P>
In the tax-free zones, industrial, commercial, agricultural and
livestock, technological and service activities will be performed
under a special system.
</P>
<P>
The similarly arranged industrial parks will allow
predominantly industrial performances and supporting services.
</P>
<P>
Concessionaires and operators of these zones will enjoy more
generous privileges in customs, banking, labor, migration and
public order, which were offered as incentives for investment.
</P>
<P>
The Executive Committee of the Council of Ministers of Cuba
will take charge of granting concessions in the tax-free zones.
</P>
<P>
The validity of the concession, 50 years at most, can be
successively extended, but will not be longer than doubling the
period originally agreed up.
</P>
<P>
While the Cuban Foreign Investment and Collaboration Ministry
largely controls the establishment of operations within the
installations in the zones, concessionaires also have a say herein.
</P>
<P>
Total exemption of taxes on income and the use of labor will be
offered to concessionaires and operators engaged in production,
manufacturing, assembling, processing of finished and semifinished
products and livestock products, during the first 12 years and a
50 percent cut during the next five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
