<HEADLINE> Red Frog Caught in Zhejiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- A rare, 7-cm-long red frog was
caught several days ago by a retired teacher in east China's
Zhejiang Province,
</P>
<P>
The frog-catcher was a biology teacher, who discovered the frog
near a grain purchasing station in Zhenghai, Zhejiang Province. He
instantly recognized the unusual species, took it home and is
raising it there, the Shanghai-based "Wenhui Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
The more than two-year-old frog is thought to be male. Its rare
red color is the result of a gene mutation, which often turns the
breed white.
</P>
<P>
"Turning red by gene mutation is a rare phenonmenon," the
teacher said, adding that he would like to give the frog to a
scientific research institute for further study.  
</P>
