<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Health Care for Farmers Improving in Xinjiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, June 7 (Xinhua) -- A large-scale project to build
hospitals in townships will provide health care for over 10
million farmers and herdsmen in west China's Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The regional government has invested 135 million yuan (16
million US dollars) to build 104 hospitals in townships and
reconstruct all the unsafe hospital buildings.
</P>
<P>
The government also provided training to 5,000 doctors, nurses
and managers, and purchased 4,000 medical instruments and 60
ambulances for the township hospitals.
</P>
<P>
About 75 percent of the region's 16 million residents are
living in farming or herding areas. In 1991, 104 out of 846
townships didn't have hospitals, and 45 percent of the hospital
buildings were in danger of collapsing.
</P>
<P>
Those hospitals were only equipped with simple medical
instruments, such as stethoscopes, sphygmomonameters and
thermometers.
</P>
<P>
Almost all the hospitals now have X-ray machines,
electrocardiographs and ultrasonic scanning machines.
</P>
<P>
Some hospitals can even perform complicated operations such as
a complete hysterectomy or cholecystomy.
</P>
<P>
The region currently has 12,000 township health workers, 8,000
village clinics and 3,500 midwives, which can provide the
preliminary health care for farmers and herdsmen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
