<HEADLINE> UN Relief Reaches Kabul Through Salang Highway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 7 (Xinhua) -- The first UN convoy since
December 1993 to cross the Salang Pass arrived in Kabul Thursday,
a report from Kabul said today.
</P>
<P>
The convoy of nine heavy trucks, which was organized by the
World Food Program (WFP), brought food and other humanitarian
supplies to the war-weary inhabitants of the Afghan capital.
</P>
<P>
The cargo included 95 tons of pulses, 23 tons of sugar, and
hoes, shovels, pickaxes, irrigation pumps as well as medicines.
</P>
<P>
The Salang Highway runs from the northern Afghan city of
Mazar-i-Sharif, which is controlled by anti-government
Junbush-i-Melli led by Rashid Dostum, to Kabul, which is in the
hands of the government led by President Burhanuddin Rabbani.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to use the Highway for humanitarian convoys, the UN
has tried hard to clear the mines on the road and to persuade the
commanders along the road to provide a safe access.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the setoff of the convoy, both Rabbani and Dostum
agreed to the opening of the road for humanitarian traffic.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the reopening of the Mazar-Samangan-Doshi-Kabul
Salang Highway will be conducive to the UN humanitarian aid to the
war-torn country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
