<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Young Monk Establishes Himself As Buddhist Singer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- A newly-marketed cassette tape here
features 16 songs recorded by a 32-year-old Chinese monk who is
also a Buddhist MTV star.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of fans now can hear the works of Zhengxing, the
first monk to establish himself by singing songs rather than
chanting scriptures, today's overseas edition of the "People's
Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
Zhengxing does not sing pop songs, but rather tunes with
Buddhist lyrics, previously performed only at temples. The young
monk believes high technology is a means to spread the religion's
popularity to more people, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, he was invited by the Xiamen Television Station
to film China's first Buddhist MTV video. The work caused a great
sensation and won a prize at a concert.
</P>
<P>
A local radio station aired a special program on Buddhist
music, using Zhengxing as the anchorman.
</P>
<P>
Prior to his monkhood, Zhengxing sang with a group in central
China. He quit the group in 1991 and became a Buddhist believer,
according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
"I have found my life's way after studying Buddhist theory. And I
think music can help promote the great religion," monk Zhengxing
explained.
</P>
<P>
He now leads a 100-member-chorus consisting of believers and
laymen, who meet every Saturday afternoon at the South Putuo
Temple in southeast China's Fujian province.
</P>
<P>
Buddhist music originated in India. It found its way into China
during the first century and later merged with traditional Chinese
music. It was extremely popular about 900 years ago.
</P>
<P>
But the musical style has experienced ups and downs as the result of
the conflicts between Buddhism, Confucianism and Taoism, as well
as wars and social chaos.
</P>
<P>
"Now, it is time to cherish the legacy," Zhengxing said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Book for Divine Warrior Printed in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, June 7 (Xinhua) -- An book of illustrations about Guan
Yu, a deified warrior who lived 1,700 years ago, has been
published in China.
</P>
<P>
The book, published by the China Today Press in both Chinese
and English, contains 180 rare pictures that illustrate the
worship of the warrior Guan Yu by his followers in Chinese
mainland, Hong Kong, Taiwan, the United States, Japan, Vietnam and
Singapore. It will be distributed in more than 130 countries and
regions.
</P>
<P>
Guan is considered a god of wealth by many businessmen,
especially in southeast Asia. The book depicts the rise from his
birth in a small village in north China's Shanxi Province, to a
god, and introduces 30 temples built in his honor.
</P>
<P>
The book was compiled by Zhu Zhengming, an official of the
United Front Work Department of the Hubei provincial committee of
the Communist Party of China. Zhu spent five years and traveled
80,000 km to collect information for the publication.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Puchu, vice-chairman of the National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference and chairman of
the Buddhist Association of China, wrote the title on the book's
cover. 
</P>
</TEXT>
