<HEADLINE> Taiwan Businessmen Establish Seedling Bases in Hainan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Taiwan businessmen have established
six seedling bases in southern China's Hainan province, which have
aided local agricultural development.
</P>
<P>
More than 60 Taiwanese-funded agricultural enterprises have
successfully bred over 40 varieties of high-quality, high-yield
plant seedlings, and improved wildlife varieties.
</P>
<P>
Each year, Taiwanese-funded enterprises in Hainan breed more
than 1,000 kilograms of plant seedlings, 10 million saplings, 300
million fry and 20,000 head of domestic breeding livestock,
according to statistics.
</P>
<P>
The six seedling bases include a pig-breeding base with an
annual production of 15,000 head; a base for breeding 50 million
nile tilapia fish from Africa, whose annual output capacity is
designed to reach 170 million; a banana and cymbidium seedling
breeding base with an annual output of one million; a vegetable
seedling breeding base producing more than 200,000 seedlings each
breeding period, and a base for breeding watermelon and mango
seedlings.
</P>
<P>
A Taiwanese-funded agricultural development company, based in
Sanya city, breeds more than 600,000 fruit and flower seedlings in
test tubes for local farmers each year.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1995, mango and banana seedlings provided by the
company had been planted in an area covering 11,000 mu (660
hectares).
</P>
<P>
Each year, the company trains more than 200 local workers in
breeding technology.  
</P>
