<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sri Lanka, South Africa Enhancing Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 7 (Xinhua)-- Sri Lanka and South Africa have
substantially enhanced their relations with the launching of
flights between Colombo and Johannesburg by Sri Lanka's flag
carrier Air Lanka and the presence of a powerful Sri Lankan
Ministerial team visiting the African country.
</P>
<P>
Air Lanka commenced a twice weekly flight to Durban and
Johannesburg on May 28 this year.
</P>
<P>
Air Lanka itself is confident of heavy passenger traffic
between Johannesburg and Colombo as there are more tourists
traveling to South Africa than a few years earlier and there is a
substantial population of Indian origin in South Africa who can be
expected to use these flights.
</P>
<P>
Besides, countries such as Maldives, India, Thailand, Malaysia
Singapore and Japan have been attracting tourists from South
Africa and the Air Lanka flights will be very convenient for them.
</P>
<P>
The visiting five member ministerial delegation included Sri
Lanka's ministers of Foreign Affairs, Industrial Development and
Trade.
</P>
<P>
The Ministerial delegation, having held fruitful talks with
their counterparts, also had discussions with the South African
Chamber of Business in Johannesburg and the two sides exchanged
views on the possibility of establishing joint ventures in both
Sri Lanka and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministers of the two countries also explored ways
and means of enhancing bilateral relations in the political and
economic fields.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan Foreign Minister Kadirgamar indicated that his
country had it in mind to open a resident diplomatic mission in
South Africa at the earliest possible time.
</P>
<P>
For its part, South Africa intended to intensify its diplomatic
 contacts with Sri Lanka and proposed to change its pattern of
concurrent accreditation by having its High Commissioner in New
Delhi oversee Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
The Ministers also discussed the Indian Ocean Rim Initiative,
The South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation, South Asian
Free Trade Area and the Southern African Development Community.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed that a Sri Lanka-South Africa Joint
Commission  at Foreign Ministerial level be set up as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
Following discussions between the two country's Trade
Ministers, Kingsley Wickremaratne of Sri Lanka and his South
African counterpart Alec Irwin, it was agreed that there should be
an exchange of trade delegations between the two countries to
explore and identify areas for economic cooperation and trade.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka's pivotal role as a springboard for penetrating the
vast and expanding South Asian market with around 450 million
middle class consumers was also seriously considered by the
Ministers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
