<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Afghan Opposition Alliance Cancels Hekmatyar's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Leader of the four-party Afghan
opposition alliance Sibghatullah Mojaddedi has decided to
terminate the membership of Hezb-i-Islami (Hekmatyar Group) from
the alliance, reports from Peshawar, Pakistan, said today.
</P>
<P>
Talking to newsmen in Peshawar after returning from Herat,
Afghanistan, Mojaddedi said that the decision was made in the wake
of Hekmatyar's re-entering into the Kabul regime led by
Burhanuddin Rabbani.
</P>
<P>
Mojaddedi said that the opposition alliance had authorized all
its component parties for holding talks with other Afghan groups.
</P>
<P>
However, it was binding that any final agreement with other
parties should be signed with the approval of the whole alliance.
</P>
<P>
After several months' negotiations with the Kabul regime,
Hekmatyar signed a reconciliation agreement with Rabbani last
month, and a Rabbani-Hekmatyar coalition government was in the
offing.
</P>
<P>
Mojaddedi accused Hekmatyar of not taking other component
parties of the alliance into confidence before signing the
agreement with Rabbani.
</P>
<P>
He also ruled out the possibility of the cooperation between
the remaining parties of his alliance and the Rabbani's regime in
the future.
</P>
<P>
The four-party opposition alliance comprises Mojaddedi's
Nejat-i-Melli, Junbush-i-Melli led by Rashid Dostum, Hezb-i-Wahdat
(Khalili Group), and Hezb-i-Islami (Hekmatyar Group).
</P>
<P>
Spokesman of the alliance in Peshawar, Talib, said that
Mojaddedi, Dostum and Khalili had held a meeting in Dostum's
headquarters, Mazar-i-Sharif, in Afghanistan and decided to
suspend Hekmatyar's membership from the alliance.
</P>
<P>
However, Hekmatyar's spokesman in Peshawar Rahman Saeed said
Thursday that his party had not been informed of the membership
suspension.
</P>
<P>
He criticized Mojaddedi for imposing his personal view on the
alliance.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> London, Dublin Agree on Chairmanship of Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The British and Irish governments
agreed today to have former U.S. senator George Mitchell presiding
over the all-party talks in Northern Ireland next week.
</P>
<P>
The agreement to choose Mitchell as the overall chairman of the
peace talks followed 48 hours of intensive negotiations between
London and Dublin.
</P>
<P>
The former senator, who will also chair a committee dealing
with the arms decommissioning of the Irish Republican Army,
currently is leading an international panel.
</P>
<P>
The panel advised Britain earlier this year on the disposal of
the weapons used in the 25-year guerrilla war between pro-British
Protestants and pro-Irish Catholics.
</P>
<P>
However, Mitchell's appointment was opposed by pro-British
unionists, whose voice was made clear by David Trimble, leader of
the Ulster Unionist Party.
</P>
<P>
"I could not and I do not agree to him having a role in these
discussions until I have been able to satisfy myself that he will
be acting in a purely independent manner," Trimble said.
</P>
<P>
Also as a result of today's London-Dublin negotiations, former
Finnish prime minister Harri Holkeri was asked to act as alternate
chairman of the committees set up for the talks.
</P>
<P>
In addition, retired Canadian General John de Chastelain was
chosen to preside over the "second strand" of the talks, which
will cover political relations between British-ruled Northern
Ireland and the Irish Republic to the south. 
</P>
</TEXT>
