<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Blackout Costs Industry Dearly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, June 7 (Xinhua)-- The 4-day power cut in Sri Lanka
last week due to a strike by electricity workers cost the
country's industrial sector a loss of 56 million US dollars,
according to the Industrial Development Ministry sources today.
</P>
<P>
The sources said this excludes the export orders the country
may have lost.
</P>
<P>
Industry had appealed for assistance to get over the power
crisis and the government has appointed a ministerial committee to
look into the matter.
</P>
<P>
The sources quoted Industrial Development Minister Gooenratne
as saying that the committee will assess the impact of the power
crisis on various sectors of the economy and study how best the
blow to the industrial sector could be cushioned.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka has been troubled by power blackouts and water supply
cutoffs from May 29 to June 1 when employees of the electricity
board went on strike to protest the government's decision to
privatize the Ceylon Electricity Board.  
</P>
</TEXT>
