<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five More HIV Cases Detected in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Five more people carrying the human
immunodeficiency virus (HIV) or suffering from acquired immune
deficiency syndrome (AIDS) were identified last month, bringing
the total number of reported cases in Indonesia to 406.
</P>
<P>
All but one of the new suffers have full-blown AIDS, the
director general of communicable diseases control said in a
statement made available to Xinhua today.
</P>
<P>
Three of the new cases were found in Irian Jaya, the eastern
most province of Indonesia, one in Jakarta and the person with HIV
lives in east Kalimantan.
</P>
<P>
There are altogether 103 people with full-blown aids -- 63 of
whom have died, and 303 HIV-positive people in Indonesia, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
Jakarta still tops the list with 140 HIV and AIDS patients,
Irian Jaya comes second with 105.
</P>
<P>
An United Nations Development Program (UNDP) report said
Indonesia might have to spend 16 billion US dollars on treatment
of AIDS sufferers if the disease could not be effectively
prevented from spreading.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Urban Poverty Worsening: ADB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 7 (Xinhua) --A sample survey by the Asian
Development Bank (ADB) has revealed an escalation of bangladesh's
urban poverty by 14.6 percent over the last five years.
</P>
<P>
The study on urban poverty in Bangladesh showed that 61.30
percent of the urban population were below the "absolute" poverty
line while 40.20 percent fell below the "hard-core" poverty line,
as compared to the corresponding figures of 46.70 percent and 26.2
percent respectively in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The questionnaire was administered to a "nationally
representative" sample of 3,000 households from Dhaka and three
other metropolitan cities as well as four secondary towns.
</P>
<P>
The study measured poverty line based on income/expenditure
related to daily normative calorie intake plus 25 percent
adjustment for non-food items. The absolute poverty line was
determined at tk 3,500 (87.5 US dollars) per household per month,
with tk 2,500 (62.5 dollars) as the poverty line for the hard-core
poor.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
