<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WEU Welcomes NATO's Plan to Boost Its Military Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 6 (Xinhua) -- President of the Assembly of the
Western European Union (WEU) Dudley Smith today welcomed NATO's
agreement to boost Europe's role within NATO.
</P>
<P>
The WEU, the 10-member European defense organization, should
not be only satisfied with its political role, he told the 41st
meeting of the WEU assembly, which was opened here Monday.
</P>
<P>
It should hold practical means to carry out various missions,
Smith asserted.
</P>
<P>
NATO reached a landmark agreement Monday in Berlin to allow the
setting up of a military component under WEU's control to
undertake European nations' own peacekeeping or relief missions.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is widely seen as the first major step by the
U.S.-led western military alliance, set up in 1949 during the Cold
War, to adapt to the new post-Cold War challenges.
</P>
<P>
Belgian Prime Minister Jean-luc Dehaene told the WEU meeting
Tuesday that securing NATO resources for WEU operations would be
among his country's main tasks when it takes over the WEU
presidency from Britain next month.
</P>
<P>
The WEU had so far concentrated on humanitarian operations, but
Belgium wanted it to raise its ambitions to peacekeeping and even
more, he said.
</P>
<P>
Dehaene pleaded again for a rapid reapproachment between the
WEU and the 15-member European Union, which was supported by
France and opposed by Britain.
</P>
<P>
"WEU must become the EU's military arm...our final objective is
a merger between the two organization, " he said. "only then will
the EU have the operational arm it need to make its policy
efficient."
</P>
<P>
The WEU, founded in March 1948 to promote European unity, now
includes Germany, Belgium, Spain, France, Greece, Italy,
Luxembourg, Holland, Britain and Portugal -- all member states of
the EU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
