<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Rejects Renewed Sanctions Against Serbia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The United States today voiced
disapproval of a request by the head of an international war
crimes tribunal to re-impose sanctions against Serbia for not
handing over the indicted Bosnian Serb war criminals.
</P>
<P>
"I think our present inclination is to give Mr. (Slobodan)
Milosevic some time to work through this problem," U.S. State
Department spokesman Nicholas Burns said at a press briefing here.
</P>
<P>
The remarks came after Antonio Cassese, head of The Hague-based
war crimes tribunal, warned in Sarajevo that he would ask the
international mediator for Bosnia reconstruction, Carl Bildt, to
reimpose tough sanctions against Serbia.
</P>
<P>
Cassese said that as one of the signatories to the Bosnian
peace agreement, Serbian President Milosevic had failed to hand
over the indicted Bosnian Serb war criminals.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 50 Bosnian Serb leaders and officials have been indicted
by the war criminals tribunal in The Hague, including Bosnian Serb
leader Radovan Karadzic and military commander General Ratko
Mladic.
</P>
<P>
Under the Bosnian peace accord, all signatories must extradite
those accused of war crimes to The Hague for trial.
</P>
<P>
Burns told the press briefing that U.S. Secretary of State
Warren Christopher had urged Milosevic at a summit meeting of the
former Yugoslav republics in Geneva on Sunday to fully comply with
the commitment he had made in the Bosnian peace accord.
</P>
<P>
"We ought to give him (Milosevic) some time now that we've laid
down this public challenge to him," the spokesman said, adding
that it would not be helpful to re-impose the sanctions against
Serbia now.
</P>
<P>
Washington would support Cassese's request only "at some point
in the future" when it finds out that Milosevic's cooperation with
the war criminals tribunal was hopeless, the spokesman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
