<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Homicides From Gunfire Up 18 Percent in 10 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Homicide cases from gunfire in
the United States increased by 18 percent in 10 years, making
firearms the cause of almost three-quarters of all homicides, the
government said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The data showed the need for more wide-ranging crime prevention
tactics, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention said.
</P>
<P>
The federal agency said 12,078 of the 19,893 homicides in the
U.S. in 1985 were committed with guns, accounting for about 61
percent of all homicides. In 1994, 17,190 of the 23,720 homicides
were pegged to gunfire, or about 72 percent of the total such
cases.
</P>
<P>
Young people fared worse. The number of murder victims aged
between 15 and 24 by guns rose by 30 percent over the last
decade. Of the 4,772 homicides in 1985 involving this age group,
3,194 were committed with guns. In 1994, 6,740 of the 7,770
homicides involved guns, the agency said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukraine Likely to Delay Closure of Chernobyl Nuclear Station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine may re-consider the timetable
for shutting down the Chernobyl Nuclear Power Station because of
delays by the G-7 group of industrialized countries in providing
agreed-on funds of three billion U.S. dollars, a senior government
minister said today.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine is to re-examine and approve the memorandums signed
with the G-7 and the European Union over the deadline of closing
down the Chernobyl station, site of the world's worst nuclear
accident, as the western nations have delayed their promised funds
for building new generators at two other nuclear power plants,
Ukraine's Minister for Environmental Protection and Nuclear
Security Yuri Kostenko said at a press conference here today.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of international pressure and continuing fears over
the Chernobyl disaster in 1986, Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma
declared in early 1995 that his country would close down the
Chernobyl Nuclear Power Station completely by the year of 2000 in
exchange for four billion U.S. dollars in aid.
</P>
<P>
In April 1996, the Moscow summit of the G-7, including the
U.S., Britain, France and Japan, and Russia agreed to provide
Ukraine with at least three billion U.S. dollars to close the
Chernobyl station, of which 500 million was for the two new
generating units.
</P>
<P>
The generators, which are expected to replace the power
supplied by the Chernobyl station, are key to closing down the
station, said Kostenko,
</P>
<P>
However, the Ukrainian minister said that so far,
negotiations over the funds with delegates from the G-7 have been
fruitless.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine's official statistics show, 4,300 people died as a
direct result of the nuclear disaster in 1986 and many of its
350,000 clean-up workers are now ill. Millions were affected,
mostly in Ukraine, Russia and Belarus and millions of acres of
land were polluted by a huge cloud of radioactive dust released
after an explosion in one of Chernobyl's nuclear reactors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
