<HEADLINE> Cubans, Africans Dominate Seville Grand Prix Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Athletes from Cuba and Africa stole
the limelight at the Grand Prix Athletics Meet in Sevile on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
With the absence of big names in the world, Cuban triple jumper
Eliecer Urrutia leapt to his victory by setting the second best of
the year in 17.70 meters.
</P>
<P>
His woman compatriot Ana Fidelia Quirot paced up to her victory
in the 800 meters with the third best time of the year in one
minute 58.93 seconds, ahead of Bulgaria's Natalya Dukovna.
</P>
<P>
Anier Garcia of Cuba won the men's 110 meters hurdles in 13.73,
beating a pair of runners from the home side to second and third,
and Norberto Tellez awarded Cuba another gold medal in the men's
800 meters in 1:45.01.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the long-distance runners in Africa still
dominated in their specialities despite challenges from the home
squad.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Wilson Kipketer set his best time of the season to win
the men's 3,000 meters steeplechase in 8:16.81, an event enabing
three runners from Kenya to stand at the podium with Richard
Barmasai and Richard Kosgei finished second and third in 8:17.09
and 8:24.49 respectively.
</P>
<P>
Moroccan Hicham El Gherroudj finished first in the men's 1,500
meters in 3:32.94, almost three seconds ahead of Spaniard Fermin
Cacho.
</P>
<P>
Paul Bitok of Kenya won the men's 5,000 meters in 13:26.49,
while Adere Birhane of Ethiopia took the women's 5,000 meters in
15:31.12.
</P>
<P>
The men's 100-meter title went to American Andre Cason in 10.30
seconds with Ghana's Emmanuel Tuffour winning the silver in 10.33
and Nigerian F. Obikwelu in third.
</P>
<P>
In the women's 100 meters, Christy Opara of Nigeria dashed
ahead first in 11.34, beating Russian Oksana Dyachenko to second.
</P>
