<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Investigates Implementation of Education Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- China is investigating the
implementation of the country's education law, according to a
report in the "People's Daily."
</P>
<P>
A group sent by the National People's Congress Standing
Committee, China's legislature, arrived in Guangzhou Wednesday to
start a nationwide check, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The new law requires local officials to view education as a
priority of the country's social and economic development plan.
</P>
<P>
According to the law, local governments should increase
educational investment and also teachers' salaries.
</P>
<P>
The deputy governor of Guangdong told the legislative group
that the law has not been challenged in the province since it was
issued last year.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government's investment in education still is
relatively low compared that in developed countries, and even some
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The investigation will target six provinces and
cities. Guangdong, the economically-prosperous southern province,
is the group's first stop, according to the paper.  
</P>
</TEXT>
