<HEADLINE> National Eye-Care Day with an Eye on Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- A forum marking the country's first
"National Eye-care Day" opened yesterday to raise the public's
awareness of protecting children and teenagers' eyesight, today's
China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Improving the eyesight of China's children will require several
changes: less homework, safer toys, better home-study
environments, and earlier diagnosis and treatment for eye
problems, the forum was told.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that about 10 million of the Chinese children
are either weak-sighted or cross-eyed. Doctors Believe that about
75 percent of them can be cured if treated at an early age.
</P>
<P>
According to Liao Wenke, who is in charge of student health
care under the State Education Commission, short-sightedness has
become a common health problem for students of all ages.
</P>
<P>
The commission's lastest national survey indicated that about
25 percent of primary-school students are near-sighted, while the
rate soars to 60 percent for students in middle schools and to 74
percent for those in institutions of higher learning.
</P>
<P>
Many students are unable to enter college or cannot study the
subjects of their choice because of eye problems, Liao said.
</P>
<P>
Over 80 physicians and government officials attended the forum,
which was sponsored by 12 state departments, including the
Ministry of Public Health, the State Education Commission, and the
China National Council of Light Industry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujian Vows to Develop Oceanic Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Southeast China's Fujian Province
will accelerate the development of its oceanic industry, making
itself a leading oceanic province.
</P>
<P>
In an inevitable development trend, the coastal province has
acquired additional resources and space from the ocean, and now
must set goals for the development of its oceanic economy, said
Jia Qinglin, a leading official of the province.
</P>
<P>
With a coastline of more than 3,300 km, the province has five
fishing grounds and more than 3,000 species of marine organisms.
The province has 125 ports along its coast, and is rich in
minerals and tidal energy resources.
</P>
<P>
Bountiful oil reserves are found in the western part of the
Taiwan Strait, according to a preliminary survey. But with its
low-level technical abilities and small-scale industries, the
province's oceanic industry is still in an early stage of
development.
</P>
<P>
Jia said there will be two development phases of the province's
oceanic industry: establishing an industry system consisting of
marine aquatic production, maritime transportation, offshore
tourism, and offshore mining industry, and listing appreciable
results in these areas by the year 2,000. The province's output
value from the oceanic industry will account for 15 percent of the
provincial gross national product.
</P>
<P>
The second phase will center on encouraging the rapid
development of the oceanic industry through advanced technology,
so that its output value will account for 30 percent of the
provincial gross national product. A series of port cities,
industrial belts, tourist zones, and foreign trade zones will be
designated along the coastal regions.
</P>
<P>
Jia attached great importance to the present development of
five areas: marine aquatic production, maritime transportation,
offshore tourism, offshore mining industry, and the utilization of
offshore islands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
