<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK, Macao, Guangdong Urged to Join Hands to Improve Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 7 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese expert has called on
the governments of south China's Guangdong Province, Hong Kong and
Macao to establish a special co-operation agency, in a move to
curb the deteriorating environment in the area.
</P>
<P>
Ma Xiaoling, an engineer with the State Bureau of Environmental
Protection, said that the worsening environment in the area could
not be effectively controlled without the co-operation of the
three regions.
</P>
<P>
The rapid development of township enterprises and the swelling
population lead to the deteriorating environment, Ma said, adding
that the mouth of the Pearl River suffers most in the pollution.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted by related departments of Guangdong Province
shows that more than 20 percent of labor-intensive enterprises
introduced into the Pearl River Delta from Hong Kong and Macao
during the past a dozen years fell into the category of polluting
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The geographical position of the three -- each borders with the
other -- determines that the contamination of one region will
inevitably affect the other two.
</P>
<P>
"Without a unified discharge standard and a limit for the total
volume of discharged waste, the environment in the area cannot be
improved in the near future," said Ma, adding that she was not
optimistic about the issue.
</P>
<P>
She pointed out that as the three regions are all planning to
set up a series of large-scale infrastructure construction
programs to meet the future needs of enlarged co-operation among
the three, especially around 1997, new pollution-related problems
are waiting ahead.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
