<HEADLINE> Philippine Army Prepares Counter-Attack on Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Philippine government troops will
counter any attacks by the MORO Islamic Liberation Front (MILF)
and the MORO National Liberation Front (MNLF) if peace talks
between the government and the Muslim rebels fail, the Business
World newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted a spokesman for the government troops as
saying that MILF forces are planning to stage bombings and retake
its former stronghold in Sultan Sa Barongis.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is also going to launch offensives on the
municipalities of Esperanza, Isulan and Tacurong in Sultan
Kudarat, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"If the dialogue between (the government) and the two groups
(MILF and MNLF) fail, we will be dealing with the secessionist
groups," he said.
</P>
<P>
"However, the government hopes for peace in Mindanao rather
than war," he said. "We will follow the policy of restraint and we
have given instructions to our soldiers to hit the MILF hard if
they attack our camps and people."
</P>
<P>
The peace talks between the government and the MNLF are
underway in the Indonesian capital of Jakarta. President Fidel
Ramos said on Wednesday that the impasse in the talks has been
broken.
</P>
<P>
The MILF and the MNLF are demanding an autonomous region
covering 13 provinces in Mindanao, but the government says that
constitutionally the demand must be put to a plebiscite.
</P>
<P>
Christians are in a clear majority in the area and there is no
chance the autonomy plan by the Muslim rebels will be accepted,
analysts said.  
</P>
