<HEADLINE> Conditions Ripe for East European Countries to Join NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUDAPEST, June 6 (Xinhua) -- NATO's delay in allowing east
European countries to join because of fears that Russia will
renege on its disarmament obligations is ridiculous, a former
U.S. defense secretary said here today.
</P>
<P>
Caspar Weinberger, who is visiting Budapest as the director of
the U.S.-based Forbes magazine, accused NATO of soft-pedalling on
its enlargment plans as Russia has repeatedly opposed the western
military alliance's eastward expansion.
</P>
<P>
He said Russia should not be allowed to exert a right of veto
over which countries can join the U.S.-led trans-Atlantic alliance.
</P>
<P>
Conditions are ripe for Hungary, the Czech Republic and Poland
to join NATO and the three former Soviet bloc countries should
have been admitted two years ago, said Weinberger, U.S. Defense
Secretary between 1981 and 1987 under the Reagan administration.
</P>
<P>
But he acknowledged that it is still too early for other east
European countries such as Romania and Bulgaria to join the
alliance, which was set up after the Second World War to counter
the Warsaw Pact countries of eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
It was a pity that the United States offered political
concessions over the issue of eastward expansion because of
Russia's sensitivity, and it was wrong for Germany to always give
in to Russia's demands, said Weinberger.
</P>
<P>
Moscow softened its opposition last week, implying at a meeting
of NATO foreign ministers in Berlin that it could live with
enlargement, provided no troops were stationed in the territories
of new members bordering with Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
