<HEADLINE> Official: UK-EU Beef Debate at Turning Point </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Malcolm
Rifkind said today that Britain's beef war with the European Union
(EU) has reached a turning point and he hoped that further
progress will be made in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a BBC Radio interview, Rifkind said, "We reached a
turning point last night in this whole problem because the Italian
government, the current EU presidency, has publicly promised to
achieve an agreement on the beef debate."
</P>
<P>
Rifkind said, "If we are making progress, then goodwill is very
much part of negotiation. If colleagues are beginning to be
helpful, it is important we should respond to that."
</P>
<P>
The EU Commission agreed on June 5 in Brussels to lift the ban
on exports of three British beef by-products -- gelatine, tallow
and bull semen as the first step to lift the ban on British beef
products exports.
</P>
<P>
As a positive response to the EU decision, Rifkind announced on
June 5 that Britain would show "good will" by not blocking the
signing of an EU association agreement with Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
However, Rifkind made it clear that "I have to emphasize that
the policy of non-cooperation with the EU can not be withdrawn
until we have that framework agreement. Nobody is going back on
that."
</P>
<P>
The British Foreign Secretary suggested that the framework for
the phased withdrawal of the total EU ban should be given before
the EU Summit due to be held in Florence, Italy, later this month.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Germany, the main force against lifting the EU ban,
remained reluctant to drop its tough stance.
</P>
<P>
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel has reportedly said that
there was no way Germany could follow Brussels by easing or
lifting the embargo and public health took priority over the
economic consequences of the ban.
</P>
<P>
The EU imposed the worldwide ban on British beef products
exports on March 27 when the British government announced that
there were possible links between BSE, or mad cow disease, and its
human equivalent Creutzfeldt-Jacob Disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
