<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwandan President to Visit China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIGALI, Rwanda, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Rwandan President Pasteur
Bizimungu today said that his scheduled China visit will further
enhance bilateral relations between Rwanda and China.
</P>
<P>
Bizimungu, who is to pay an official visit to China between
June 10 and 14, told Kigali-based Chinese journalists that he will
extend gratitude to the Chinese leaders and people for their
support and aid in Rwanda's reconstruction after the civil war.
</P>
<P>
China supported Rwanda politically, morally and materially when
the country started reconstruction in 1994 after the civil war
ended, the president said.
</P>
<P>
China was one of the first foreign countries which had reopened
their embassies in Kigali immediately after the civil war ended,
he added.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan president said that his country is stable now since
security has greatly improved and the Rwandan people have made
decisive progress in developing economy and social welfare.
</P>
<P>
Seventy percent of agricultural output had been restored by the
beginning of this year while highways, water and electricity
supplies as well as telecommunication facilities, which were
severely damaged during the war, had been basically rehabilitated.
</P>
<P>
The president said that though the country is resettling
upwards two million refugees, there are still 1.5 million Rwandan
refugees staying abroad.
</P>
<P>
Bizimungu said that he wishes China would continue to support
and aid his country at a time when it braves various difficulties
to rehabilitate its economy and to reconstruct its infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Civil war broke out in Rwanda on April 6, 1994 when its
president was killed in a plane crash and the three-month civil
war forced millions of Rwandans to flee their homes and seek
refuge in neighboring countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
