<HEADLINE> Barings Futures' Auditors Face Billion-Dollar Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's largest law suit,
involving more than 1.43 billion US dollars, has been served on
the auditors of the Baring Futures Singapore Ltd. (BFS) for
negligence leading to last year's collapse of the Baring plc.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper Business Times today, lawyers from
Rajah &AMP; Tann served the papers Monday against external auditors
Cooper &AMP; Lybrand Singapore and Deloitte &AMP; Touch.
</P>
<P>
It said that Barings' administrators in England had earlier
also filed claims against the London offices of the two external
auditors.
</P>
<P>
Barings collapsed in late February last year after Nick Leeson,
BFS' general manager, racked up losses of more than 2.2 billion
Singapore dollars (about 1.57 billion US dollars) trading in
Nikkei and Japanese government bond futures and options.
</P>
<P>
The two auditors are being sued not just for negligence in
relation to the merchant bank's collapse but also for failing to
detect Leeson's secret account 88888.
</P>
<P>
Leeson is now serving a six-and-a-half-year jail term here
after being found guilty of fraud charges.  
</P>
</TEXT>
