<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Urged to Reinstate Death Penalty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria's new interior minister
today appealed to the country's National Assembly (parliament) to
reinstate death penalty to curb rampaging lethal crimes.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Nikolai Dobrev made a written appeal to
parliament speaker Blagovest Sendov and said that some 2,300
people were killed by criminals in the past five years during
which period a total of one million crimes were committed.
</P>
<P>
88 Innocent people fell victims to deadly criminals in the
first quarter of this year including five policemen who were
killed while trying to stop criminals.
</P>
<P>
On the rise in the past few years were crimes such as bomb
blasts, assassinations, kidnappings, rapes and armed robberies
which have reached an unprecedented level, the interior minister
stressed in his appeal.
</P>
<P>
Dobrev blamed the increase of crimes on the malfunction and
misfunction of government departments as well as on the abolition
of capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
The interior minister urged the parliament to revise its 1990
law which abolished death penalty and reinstate it to tighten law
enforcement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
