<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chechen Rebels Soften Stance on Russian Troops' Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Chechen rebels today softened their
hardline stance on the withdrawal of Russian troops, saying they
were ready to conditionally accept Moscow's proposal to pull out
in exchange for simultaneous disarmament by the separatists.
</P>
<P>
Rebel delegates told Russian officials during peace talks that
as a precondition, an accord to this effect should be signed with
guarantees provided by the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) which is mediating in the talks, the
Itar-Tass news agency said.
</P>
<P>
But the agency did not report on Russian officials' reaction to
the offer by the rebels, who have insisted that they will lay down
arms only after an immediate pullout of the federal troops from
the breakaway republic of Chechnya. The rebels are also demanding
that Chechnya be demilitarized after their disarmament.
</P>
<P>
Itar-Tass said the two sides failed to make any progress during
their three-day tough talks which ended today in Nazran, capital
of the Ingushetia region bordering Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
But it added that the talks, aimed at discussing the details of
a broad peace deal struck in Moscow May 27, are due to reopen in
Nazran Sunday.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Russian officials refused to discuss rebel
demands to cancel the June 16 Chechen parliamentary election,
saying it is an internal affair of the Chechen government.
</P>
<P>
The two sides failed to sign accords on the exchange of
prisoners of war and a ceasefire as stipulated in the Moscow peace
deal signed by President Boris Yeltsin and rebel leader Zelimkhan
Yandarbiyev last week. But a truce took effect in the region on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Chechen conflict flared up in December 1994 when Yeltsin
ordered troops and tanks into the republic to quash the
independence bid by Yandarbiyev's predecessor Dzhokhar Dudayev.
</P>
<P>
The 18-month war has killed about 30,000 people, including
civilians and fighters on both sides, and uprooted tens of
thousands of Chechen people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
