<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Cuts Interest Rates to 5.75 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of England, the central
bank of Britain, took financial markets by surprise today by
cutting its interest rates by 0.25 percent to 5.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
The cut, the fourth since last December, followed an unusually
long monthly meeting on Wednesday between Chancellor of the
Exchequer Kenneth Clarke and Bank of England governor Eddie George.
</P>
<P>
Clarke, who has the final say on the government's monetary
policy, said in a statement that the decision was justified by low
inflation and "below-trend" economic growth.
</P>
<P>
"I have decided another quarter percent cut in interest rates
is sensible. Cost pressures have eased further and the economy is
growing below trend," the Chancellor said.
</P>
<P>
He is still confident of hitting the government's inflation
target of below 2.5 percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
However, some economists said that the move by the Conservative
government was politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
Although industry is in the doldrums, they noted, the much
larger service sector is performing well and consumer spending is
picking up, so there is little need for the stimulus of a rate cut.
</P>
<P>
Facing a general election within a year and lagging badly in
opinion polls behind the opposition Labor Party, experts said, the
government is desperate to do all it can to win back voters.
</P>
<P>
Responding to the Bank of England's lower official interest
rates, Britain's commercial banks by cutting their base lending
rates by the same amount to 5.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Halifax Building Society, the country's biggest
home loan company, cut its key mortgage rate to 6.99 percent from
7.25 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
