<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Phonetic Symbols Make Reading Easier for Blinds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Blind people in China are to drop
the braille they have used for over 40 years. It will be replaced
by a new kind of written language marked with the tones
of Chinese characters.
</P>
<P>
The State Language Commission has approved to widespread use of
the new braille among 7.5 million blind people during the next
five years.
</P>
<P>
The current Chinese braille has contributed much to
communication for blind people since it was introduced in 1953.
</P>
<P>
However the braille does not indicate the tones of the Chinese
characters, and blind people have to figure out the pronunciation
and meaning of words through context, which makes it extremely
difficult for them to understand classical Chinese and scientific
articles.
</P>
<P>
The inventor of the present braille, Huang Nai, headed a group
of linguists and blind scholars, to carry out study on a new kind
of language.
</P>
<P>
After twenty years of hard work, they invented the new braille,
which has clearer shape and more accurate pronunciation than the
old one, and is more convenient for the automatic shift to the
normal Chinese characters and computer operations.
</P>
<P>
All new books for the blind will be published in the new braille
by the year 1998, and all the blind schools will use it by the
year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0280 </DOCNO>
