<HEADLINE> Beijing's 16 Taxi Companies Ordered to Stop Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- More than 50 Beijing taxi drivers
have been forced off the road after complaints from customers.
</P>
<P>
And 16 operators have had their businesses halted following
claims of mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
Beijing taxi authorities have intensified inspections and
punishments on the capital's taxi trade in a bid to improve the
service.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of the year the driving licenses of 51 taxi
drivers were cancelled after complaints by passengers.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Yingxi, director of Beijing Municipal Taxi Administrative
Bureau, said that the bureau will continue to enforce regulations
and punish taxi drivers who cheat passengers.
</P>
<P>
The regulations state that drivers who notch up two complaints
from passengers will be fined or have their driving licenses
suspended. Serious violators will have their driving licenses
cancelled by public security departments.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhang more than 89,000 taxis have been inspected
during the first five months of this year. More than 5,000 taxis
were found to have violated regulations and 1,104 drivers had
their licenses suspended.
</P>
<P>
Examination on management of taxi companies is also being
strengthened, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
Beijing now has more than 1,600 taxi companies, over 60,000
taxis and more than 80,000 taxi workers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
