<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-US Medical Center Benefits Near-sighted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- A Sino-American joint venture for
vision correction has performed operations to 30 near-sighted
people and sharply improved their eye-sight.
</P>
<P>
The vision correction center, which is jointly sponsored by
No.1 affiliated hospital of the Dalian Medical University and the
American E-TOOR Corporation, uses Photo Refractive Keratectomy
(PRK) machines and other instruments to treat near-sightedness,
far-sightedness, astigmia and keratopathy.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that nearly 300 million people in China are
near-sighted, with the incidence rate of near-sightedness reaching
40 percent in some big cities.
</P>
<P>
Scientists say that PRK, which uses an ultraviolet light to cut
the cornea surface to concave shape, is a safe and effective
method of improving eye sight.
</P>
<P>
PRK is currently used in over 50 countries around the world.
The Food and Medicine Bureau of the United States has approved the
clinical use of the PRK.
</P>
<P>
Dalian is one of the first cities in north China to open such a
vision correction center.
</P>
<P>
The center has invited American doctors to guarantee the
operation techniques and ensure the operations go smoothly.
</P>
<P>
Many near-sighted people in China have expressed an interest in
the operation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Perry: Brown Killed in Multi-Factor Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. Commerce Secretary
Ron Brown was killed in an accident caused by a deadly combination
of factors including questionable pilot decisions, U.S. Defense
Secretary William Perry said today.
</P>
<P>
The Pentagon chief made the remarks in an interview with
American reporters aboard his plane en route from Europe.
</P>
<P>
"It was not one single problem or mistake," Perry said. "There
was a string of events which led to the accident."
</P>
<P>
Brown was killed on April 3 when he was flying a U.S. Air Force
plane to visit Croatia with a group of leading American business
executives. The plane slammed into a rocky mountain peak near
Dubrovnik airport and no one survived.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Air Force has since been investigating the accident.
The finding will be made public Friday, Pentagon officials said.
</P>
<P>
Perry told the reporters that Beside doubtful decisions by the
pilot, contributing factors were Air Force leaders' failure to
certify the airport as safe in advance, insufficient navigational
guidance from the airport, and a wind that caused the plane to
drift off the regular course.
</P>
<P>
But Perry said that the full story may never be known as the
old-fashion military plane had no data or voice recorders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
