<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Invests More in Water Conservancy Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 7 (Xinhua) -- China has invested over 29 billion
yuan on water conservancy projects since last winter, latest
statistics from the Ministry of Water Conservancy reveal.
</P>
<P>
The construction of the projects will provide favorable
conditions for this year's agriculture harvests and anti-flood
struggles in the flood season, according to the ministry.
</P>
<P>
By the end of March 660,000 hectares of land had been newly
provided with irrigation facilities, with irrigation facilities
across another four million hectares improved.
</P>
<P>
Since last winter 1.6 million hectares of middle and
low-yielding arable land have been transformed and soil erosion on
27,000 square kilometers has been curbed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile some 12.5 million more people have been provided with
clean drinking water.
</P>
<P>
The measure of water-saving irrigation has been spread all
across China, especially in the drought areas such as Shaanxi and
Gansu provinces, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Provinces suffering from floods last year, such as Liaoning,
Jilin, Hubei and Anhui provinces, have spared no efforts to
reconstruct the water-conservancy projects.
</P>
<P>
So far 80 percent of the projects demolished by last year's
floods have been reconstructed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
