<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archeologists Discover 8,000 Years Old Totems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, June 7 (Xinhua) -- Archeologists in China have
discovered two 8,000-year-old dragon totems.
</P>
<P>
The totems, or statues of animals worshiped by primitive
tribes, were excavated at Yangjiawazi village in west Liaoning
province. They are obviously two dragons.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists said that one dragon is 1.2 meters long and the
other is 0.8 meters long. Both of them were made of yellow soil,
and their mouths look like those of ducks and with tails like
those of fish.
</P>
<P>
China is often called the country of dragons. But scholars have
been arguing over why the ancestors adored dragons so
much. Archeologists said the discovery, first of its kind in the
country, will help to study the origins of the mysterious
culture.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Shares Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Stocks on Wall Street moved lower
today as investors still worried that Friday's key employment
report will include inflationary trends.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial fell 30.29 points to close at
5,667.19.
</P>
<P>
Broad-market indexes also turned lower after a strong opening.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a margin of more than
4-to-3.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume totaled 463.13 million shares, up from 375.38
million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE's composite index fell 2.28 to 361.10 and the Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 5.41 to 673.03.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index fell 14.48 to 1,234.67 and the
American Stock Exchange's market value index fell 5.43 to 602.84.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq market retreated from Wednesday's record close as
key technology issues such as Intel, Sun Microsystems and Cisco
Systems declined.
</P>
<P>
Technology shares were also weak on the NYSE. IBM was one of
the weakest Dow components.
</P>
<P>
The financial markets have plunged after recent strong
employment reports which could be understood as strong spending
and, consequently higher inflation. Friday's report would
reinforce fears the Federal Reserve will fight inflation by
raising short-term interest rates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
