<HEADLINE> Over 40,000 UNITA Soldiers Quartered in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Over 40,000 soldiers of the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) have
been quartered so far, a U.N. spokeswoman said here today.
</P>
<P>
Sylvana Foa said at a news briefing that 1,261 UNITA soldiers
were quartered Wednesday, bringing the total of quartered UNITA
soldiers to 40,631.
</P>
<P>
The UNITA had promised to quarter 50,000 of its troops by June
15.
</P>
<P>
The UNITA has some 60,000 troops. Quartering of UNITA troops is
the key element for the peace process in Angola, which has been
plagued by armed conflicts for three decades.
</P>
<P>
Both the Security Council and Secretary General Boutros
Boutros-Ghali have repeatedly urged the Angolan government and
the UNITA to implement the Lusaka Protocol, especially accelerating
the pace of quartering troops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
