<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 60 Released Croatian Serbs Arrive in Belgrade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Sixty out of the 76 Serbs pardoned
by the Croatian government on May 30 arrived here today, after
spending nearly one year in Croatian prisons.
</P>
<P>
The Serbs were arrested in August 1995 when the government
troops launched a massive offensive against the self-styled Serb
Krajina Republic in Croatia and more than 250,000 Serbs fled the
northern and southern parts of Serb Krajina as a result of the
military operation.
</P>
<P>
The Croatian government issued an amnesty law last week
pardoning Serb soldiers who were arrested by the government
troops.
</P>
<P>
President of the Yugoslav Commission for Humanitarian Issues
and Missing Persons Pavle Todorovic, who welcomed the group, said
he was dissatisfied with the Croatian government because more than
250 Serbs were still held in Croatian prisons, according to the
Tanjug news agency.
</P>
<P>
The Croatian side constantly politicizes the problems of
prisoners and missing persons, Todorovic said. He urged the
international community to put pressure on the Croatian government
to fulfill basic humanitarian law obligations and release the
detained Serbs.
</P>
<P>
Most of the Serbs who arrived here did not speak to reporters
in fear of possible retaliation against the Serbs remaining in
Croatian prisons. But those who did speak said they had
experienced worst treatments in the prison in Karlovac, a town
about 50 km southwest of Zagreb, Tanjug added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US House of Representatives Approves Wisconsin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Republicans in the U.S. House of
Representatives today pushed through a bill granting fast-track
approval to Wisconsin's welfare overhaul plan, a move Democrats
called election-year politics.
</P>
<P>
The 289-136 vote authorized Wisconsin to implement a dramatic
plan to move people from welfare to work only eight days after
Wisconsin Governor Tommy Thompson formally requested federal
waivers so the experiment could begin.
</P>
<P>
"The president endorsed the Wisconsin proposal, now we are
giving him the opportunity to personally approve it by signing
this bill," said Ways and Means Chairman Bill Archer, a
Republican, in explaining the congressional intervention in what
normally is an executive branch decision.
</P>
<P>
Democrats said that President Bill Clinton has granted waivers
to 38 states, including Wisconsin, to carry out limited welfare
reform experiments, and there was no purpose in the legislation
other than to embarrass the president.
</P>
<P>
In his May 18 radio address, Clinton spoke highly of the
Wisconsin plan as one of the most innovative being proposed by
state legislatures.
</P>
<P>
Republicans accused Clinton of trying to steal a Republican
issue just before presumptive Republican presidential nominee Bob
Dole was to make a major address on welfare in Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
Under the Social Security Act, the Agriculture and Health and
Human Services departments may waive federal regulations for state
programs as long as the programs meet the objectives of federal
assistance. Congress also has the authority to grant specific
waivers.
</P>
<P>
The Wisconsin waivers will still have to be approved by the
Senate and signed by the president.
</P>
<P>
White House press secretary Mike McCurry said the bill would
have no impact on the people of Wisconsin before 1997. He
reiterated the White House policy of trying to review the waiver
requests within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
A larger debate is expected in the coming weeks over the reform
of the national welfare system. Republicans want to link welfare
and Medicaid, providing block grants to the states and letting
them run the programs.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has promised to make major changes in welfare with the
emphasis on giving people the training and jobs they need to get
off welfare rolls, but he has twice vetoed Republican welfare
bills on the grounds that they would eliminate federal guarantees
protecting welfare recipients and their children.
</P>
<P>
The "Wisconsin Works" plan will require most welfare recipients
to get jobs, providing subsidies to employers who hire them and
community service jobs for those who can't find work on their own.
</P>
<P>
It also will eliminate Medicaid and replace it with a health
care plan for the poor through the state's existing health
maintenance organization system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Rejects Balanced-Budget Constitutional Amendment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate rejected a
balanced-budget constitutional amendment today, as Republicans and
Democrats waged an election-year duel over who could seem most
sincere about erasing federal deficits.
</P>
<P>
The Senate voted the proposed amendment with 64-35. That was
two votes shy of the two-thirds margin required for approval of an
amendment to the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-two Republicans and 12 Democrats voted for the amendment,
while 34 Democrats and one Republican voted no. Sen. Claiborne
Pell from Rhode Island did not vote.
</P>
<P>
The outgoing Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole knew the attempt
would fail but hoped it would embarrass President Clinton and
other Democrats in the U.S. Congress.
</P>
<P>
"It's not whether you win or lose, but whether you've made the
statement," said Dole, who will resign from the Senate in five
days to campaign fulltime for the U.S. presidency.
</P>
<P>
Republicans in U.S. Congress said the amendment would provide
the pressure needed to force lawmakers to find the savings
needed to end the huge budget deficit that have saddled the U.S.
government since 1969.
</P>
<P>
But Democrats argued that with Republicans and Clinton having
each proposed plans for erasing government deficits by 2002, what
is needed is a bipartisan agreement, not a change in the
Constitution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
