<DOCNO> XIE19960607.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Military Spending Drops Sharply, IMF Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Military spending worldwide
dropped to a low of 2.4 percent of world GDP in 1995 from 3.6
percent in 1990, according to the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
The latest issue of Survey, a publication of IMF, said that the
decline in military spending has been widespread both
geographically and by level of development based on data of 130
countries.
</P>
<P>
Survey listed figures of different groups as follows:
</P>
<P>
-- Military spending by developed countries as a group fell to
2.4 percent of the GDP in 1995 from 3.2 percent in 1990;
</P>
<P>
-- Developing countries as a group cut their military spending
nearly in half as a share of GDP -- to 2.6 percent in 1995 from
4.9 percent in 1990;
</P>
<P>
-- The transition economies registered the most dramatic
decline in military expenditures, trimming from 7.9 percent of GDP
to 3 percent;
</P>
<P>
-- African countries steadily reduced their spending to 2.1
percent of GDP in 1995 from 3 percent five years earlier;
</P>
<P>
-- Asian countries sustained their reduction in military
spending by equivalent of 0.5 percentage point of GDP to 2.3
percent in 1995;
</P>
<P>
-- Latin American countries maintained their military spending
at about 1.2 percent of GDP, the lowest share in the world; and
</P>
<P>
-- Europe and Developing countries in the Middle East, which
historically have recorded the highest levels of military
spending, reduced such expenditures from 8.8 percent to 7 percent
of GDP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
