<DATE_TIME> 1996-06-07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar at 28-Month High Against Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 6 (Xinhua) -- Surprise interest rate cuts in
Europe sent the U.S. dollar to a 28-month high against the
Japanese yen Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In New York, the dollar traded at 109.21 yen at the closing,
compared with 109.02 yen late Wednesday. During the day, the
dollar climbed as high as 109.52 yen, the highest level since Feb.
4, 1994, when it was quoted at 109.60 yen.
</P>
<P>
The dollar traded at 1.5296 German marks late Thursday in New
York, compared with 1.5308 marks Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Bank of England chiseled out a 25-percentage point cut in
its base lending rate to 5.75 percent. The British rate cut was a
surprise partly because analysts saw it as motivated by
Conservative Party desires to improve its standing before
elections occur sometime before May 1997.
</P>
<P>
While the Danes also cut short term rates, the French cut was
considered more justified because France is trying to balance its
books to enable its entry into European monetary union in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
